# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adam-style
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adam-style/adam-style] The **Adam style** (also called **Adamesque** or the **Style of the Brothers Adam**) is an 18th-century neoclassical style of interior design and architecture, as practised by Scottish architect William Adam and his sons, of whom Robert (1728–1792) and James (1732–1794) were the most widely known.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] The Adam brothers advocated an integrated style for architecture and interiors, with walls, ceilings, fireplaces, furniture, fixtures, fittings and carpets all being designed by the Adams as a single uniform scheme.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] Their style is commonly known under the mistaken plural "Adams style".
[src:adam-style/adam-style] The style was superseded from around 1795 onwards by the Regency style and the French Empire style.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] During the 18th century there was much work for eager architects and designers, as Britain experienced a boom in the building of new houses, theatres, shops, offices and factories, with towns growing rapidly due to the onset of the Industrial Revolution.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] The emphasis was on modernisation, with regulations being introduced to clean up the nation's streets, promoting the re-paving of roads and pavements, improving drainage and street lighting, and better fireproofing of buildings with the widespread use of brick and stone.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] Speculative building was rife, with some developers focussing on high speed and low cost.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] Sometimes, newly built houses collapsed due to poor workmanship; whilst others continually shifted on their foundations, giving rise to the phrase "things that go bump in the night", as mysterious crashes, creaks and thuds were heard by their inhabitants late at night.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] London experienced major expansion, with the newly built West End, which included the elegant squares of Mayfair; areas of the East End of London were also developed, such as the new terraces in Spitalfields.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] The cities of Edinburgh, Bristol and Dublin were all expanded and modernised.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] Birmingham was described in 1791 as being the "first manufacturing town in the world".
[src:adam-style/adam-style] Manchester and Liverpool each saw their population triple between 1760 and 1800.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] New towns, like Bath, were constructed around natural spas.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] Old medieval cities and market towns, such as York and Chichester, had their buildings re-fronted with brick or stucco, plus new sash windows, to give the impression of modernity, despite the underlying structures remaining medieval.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] The Neoclassical style was all the vogue throughout the 18th century, and many style guides were published to advise builders how their finished properties should look.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] Architects, designers, cabinet makers, stonemasons, and craftsmen published pattern books and style guides to advertise their ideas, thereby hoping to attract a lucrative clientele.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] The work of the Adam brothers set the style for domestic architecture and interiors for much of the latter half of the 18th century.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] Robert and James Adam travelled in Italy and Dalmatia in the 1750s, observing the ruins of the classical world.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] On their return to Britain, they set themselves up with their older brother, John, as architects.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] Robert and James published a book entitled *The Works in Architecture* in instalments between 1773 and 1779.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] This book of engraved designs made the *Adam* repertory available throughout Europe.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] The Adam brothers aimed to simplify the rococo and baroque styles which had been fashionable in the preceding decades, to bring what they felt to be a lighter and more elegant feel to Georgian houses.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] *The Works in Architecture* illustrated the main buildings the Adam brothers had worked on and crucially documented the interiors, furniture and fittings, designed by the Adams.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] A parallel development of this phase of neoclassical design is the French Louis XVI style.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] Artists such as Angelica Kauffman and Antonio Zucchi were employed to paint classical figurative scenes within cartouches set into the interior walls and ceilings.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] So many able designers were working in this style in London from circa 1770 that the style is currently more usually termed *Early Neoclassical*.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] It was typical of *Adam style* to combine decorative neo-Gothic details into the classical framework.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] So-called "Egyptian" and "Etruscan" design motifs were minor features.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] The Adam style was superseded from around 1795 onwards by the simpler Regency style in Britain; and the French Empire style in France and Russia, which was a more imperial and self-consciously archeological style, connected with the First French Empire.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] Interest in the Adam style was revived in the late Victorian and Edwardian eras, initiated by a spectacular marquetry cabinet by Wright & Mansfield exhibited at the Paris Exposition of 1867.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] Reproduction furniture in the general "Regency Revival" style, to which the Adam revival was closely linked, was very popular with the expanding middle classes from circa 1880 to 1920.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] They were attracted to the light and elegant designs, as a contrast to the heavier and more cluttered interiors which had dominated their homes during the second half of the 19th century.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] The revival competed with the Arts and Crafts style, which continued to be popular in Britain up to the 1930s.
[src:adam-style/adam-style] The Adam and Regency revivals, however, lost mainstream momentum after World War I, being replaced by Art Deco in popular taste.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Elements such as whole, split, or peeled logs, bark, roots, and burls, along with native granite fieldstone, were used to build interior and exterior components.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Massive fireplaces and chimneys built of cut stone are also common within the Great Camp architecture.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] The use of native building materials was not only for promoting a natural appearance, but also to avoid the expense of transporting conventional building materials into a remote location.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] The style drew upon Swiss chalet architecture, which had been introduced to America by Andrew Jackson Downing around 1850.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Log construction was popularized by Downing's protégé, Calvert Vaux, in his pattern book *Villas and Cottages* in 1857.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Downing's design principles emphasized utility, structural expression, and conformity to natural surroundings.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] The building form was influenced by Stick style, but using log framing instead of dimensional lumber to express the structural system of the buildings.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Charles Eastlake's book *Hints on Household Taste in Furniture, Upholstery and other Details* also influenced the Adirondack rustic style.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Interior decorations such as rustic and Mission Style furniture, mounted trophies of fish and game, Japanese fans and screens, and American Indian artifacts were influenced by Eastlake's ideas.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Camp Santanoni, Newcomb, New York, built for Robert C.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Pruyn of Albany, was the first Adirondack camp to be comprehensively designed as a unit by a professional architect, Robert Henderson Robertson of New York, who designed the Main Camp Complex.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] In Adirondack Architecture, many sites, buildings, and lodges are referred to as 'camps'.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] A camp can refer to any area in which people can find shelter and gather in one location for an extended period of time.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] The word 'camp' dates back to the early days of Adirondack exploration.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Hunters, homesteaders, explorers, and loggers in the area would establish temporary campsites as a place to meet, rest, and eat.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] These early camps initially featured temporary, scattered, open-air structures which later on evolved to semi-permanent canvas tents which sat atop a wooden platform.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] These tents were suited for resting, relaxing, and cooking, and were even heated by fireplaces.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] As logging became more predominant in the area, large companies of loggers required larger camps with features such as dormitories, a mess hall, and even stables.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] The logging camps featured basic log buildings which were meant to last until the area had been logged, then were left to rot.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] By 1850, New York had become the most heavily logged state in the entire country.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] The rapid growth of the logging industry demanded larger inns for the loggers to stay at which created demand for logging camps to become more permanent.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] The first permanent structures were constructed by Adirondack guides and early settlers using only logs from the area and hand tools.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] These early log cabins became popular with hunters and explorers in the area, as they would pay the cabin owners for a warm place to stay.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Many travelers would come to the area to find a place to get away from everyday life and travel by foot to enjoy a comfortable stay in a simple log cabin, surrounded by nature.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Tales of these Adirondack getaways started being published in books which became very popular with the general public.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Demand for these permanent structures increased as more people migrated to the area, and soon, log camps featuring multiple buildings all in one area had been established and were known as 'commercial camps'.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] By the 1890s commercial camps had grown so popular that some featured three-story hotel style buildings.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Despite major growth, these sites were still referred to as 'camps' as they offered a rustic, outdoor experience unlike other resort hotels.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Eventually, wealthy visitors purchased large lots of land and established private 'family camps' featuring a large central building or lodge called the 'main camp' which would often be surrounded by up to a dozen smaller, separate buildings used for sleeping, dining, laundry, cooking, etc.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] By the beginning of the 1900s, development of roads, railroads, and advanced building methods made it affordable for middle class families to purchase land and build a camp in the Adirondacks.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] As development in the Adirondacks continued, many of the new structures built were not entire compounds, but single structures for a single family, however the term 'camp' is still used to describe all buildings of this style in the region.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] Most camps to this day are still constructed of natural materials such as wood and stone, and have a predominant focus on the wild nature of the early exploration days of the Adirondacks.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] The Adirondacks buildings were recognized for their rugged finish and outstanding craftsmanship especially by the wealthy locals.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] The Adirondacks style of architecture can be specialized into custom homes, rugged roofing, log cabins, boat houses, rustic furnishing, rustic kitchen, birch and cedar furniture, log and twig works.
[src:adam-style/adirondack-architecture] This style of architecture is found most prominently in and around the area of Adirondack Park.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Adobe architecture has been dated to before 5,100 BP.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Adobe bricks are rectangular prisms small enough that they can quickly air dry individually without cracking.
[src:adam-style/adobe] They can be subsequently assembled, with the application of adobe mud to bond the individual bricks into a structure.
[src:adam-style/adobe] There is no standard size, with substantial variations over the years and in different regions.
[src:adam-style/adobe] In some areas a popular size measured 20 cm × 10 cm × 30 cm (8 by 4 by 12 inches) weighing about 10 kg (25 pounds); in other contexts the size is 25 cm × 10 cm × 36 cm (10 by 4 by 14 inches) weighing about 15 kg (35 pounds).
[src:adam-style/adobe] The maximum sizes can reach up to 45 kg (100 pounds); above this weight it becomes difficult to move the pieces, and it is preferred to ram the mud *in situ*, resulting in a different typology known as rammed earth.
[src:adam-style/adobe] In dry climates, adobe structures are extremely durable, and account for some of the oldest existing buildings in the world.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Adobe buildings offer significant advantages due to their greater thermal mass, but they are known to be particularly susceptible to earthquake damage if they are not reinforced.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Cases where adobe structures were widely damaged during earthquakes include the 1976 Guatemala earthquake, the 2003 Bam earthquake, and the 2010 Chile earthquake.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Buildings made of sun-dried earth are common throughout the world (Middle East, Western Asia, North Africa, West Africa, South America, Southwestern North America, Southwestern and Eastern Europe.).
[src:adam-style/adobe] Adobe had been in use by indigenous peoples of the Americas in the Southwestern United States, Mesoamerica, and the Andes for several thousand years.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Puebloan peoples built their adobe structures with handsful or basketsful of adobe, until the Spanish introduced them to making bricks.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Adobe bricks were used in Spain from the Late Bronze and Iron Ages (eighth century BCE onwards).
[src:adam-style/adobe] Its wide use can be attributed to its simplicity of design and manufacture, and economics.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The word *adobe* /əˈdoʊbiː/ has existed for around 4,000 years with relatively little change in either pronunciation or meaning.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The word can be traced from the Middle Egyptian (c.
[src:adam-style/adobe] 2000 BC) word *ḏbt* "mud brick" (with vowels unwritten).
[src:adam-style/adobe] Middle Egyptian evolved into Late Egyptian and finally to Coptic (c.
[src:adam-style/adobe] 600 BC), where it appeared as ⲧⲱⲃⲉ *tōbə*.
[src:adam-style/adobe] This was adopted into Arabic as الطوب *aṭ-ṭawbu* or *aṭ-ṭūbu*, with the definite article *al-* attached to the root *tuba*.
[src:adam-style/adobe] This was assimilated into the Old Spanish language as *adobe* [aˈdobe], probably via Mozarabic.
[src:adam-style/adobe] English borrowed the word from Spanish in the early 18th century, still referring to mudbrick construction.
[src:adam-style/adobe] In more modern English usage, the term *adobe* has come to include a style of architecture popular in the desert climates of North America, especially in New Mexico, regardless of the construction method.
[src:adam-style/adobe] An adobe brick is a composite material made of earth mixed with water and an organic material such as straw or dung.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The soil composition typically contains sand, silt, and clay.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Straw is useful in binding the brick together and allowing the brick to dry evenly, thereby preventing cracking due to uneven shrinkage rates through the brick; dung offers the same advantage.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The most desirable soil texture for producing the mud of adobe is 15% clay, 10–30% silt, and 55–75% fine sand.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Another source quotes 15–25% clay and the remainder sand and coarser particles up to cobbles 50 to 250 mm (2 to 10 in), with no deleterious effect.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Modern adobe is stabilized with either emulsified asphalt or Portland cement up to 10% by weight.
[src:adam-style/adobe] No more than half the clay content should be expansive clays, with the remainder non-expansive illite or kaolinite.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Too much expansive clay results in uneven drying through the brick, resulting in cracking, while too much kaolinite will make a weak brick.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Typically the soils of the Southwest United States, where such construction has been widely used, are an adequate composition.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Adobe walls are load bearing, meaning that they carry their own weight into the foundation rather than through another structure, hence the adobe must have sufficient compressive strength.
[src:adam-style/adobe] In the United States, most building codes call for a minimum compressive strength of 2.1 N/mm2 (300 lbf/in2) for the adobe block.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Adobe construction should be designed so as to avoid lateral structural loads that would cause bending loads.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The building codes require the building sustain a 1 gram (0.035 oz) lateral acceleration earthquake load.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Such an acceleration will cause lateral loads on the walls, resulting in shear and bending and inducing tensile stresses.
[src:adam-style/adobe] To withstand such loads, the codes typically call for a tensile modulus of rupture strength of at least 2.1 N/mm2 (300 lbf/in2) for the finished block.
[src:adam-style/adobe] In addition to being an inexpensive material with a small resource cost, adobe can serve as a significant heat reservoir due to the thermal properties inherent in the massive walls typical in adobe construction.
[src:adam-style/adobe] In climates typified by hot days and cool nights, the high thermal mass of adobe mediates the high and low temperatures of the day, moderating the temperature of the living space.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The massive walls require a large and relatively long input of heat from the sun (radiation) and from the surrounding air (convection) before they warm through to the interior.
[src:adam-style/adobe] After the sun sets and the temperature drops, the warm wall will continue to transfer heat to the interior for several hours due to the time-lag effect.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Thus, a well-planned adobe wall of appropriate thickness is very effective at controlling inside temperature through the wide daily fluctuations typical of desert climates, a factor which has contributed to its longevity as a building material.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Thermodynamic material properties have significant variation in the literature.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Some experiments suggest that the standard consideration of conductivity is not adequate for this material, as its main thermodynamic property is inertia, and conclude that experimental tests should be performed over a longer period of time than usual – preferably with changing thermal jumps.
[src:adam-style/adobe] There is an effective R-value for a north facing 10-inch (25 cm) wall of R0=10 hr ft2 °F/Btu, which corresponds to thermal conductivity k=10 in x 1 ft/12 in /R0=0.33 Btu/(hr ft °F) or 0.57 W/(m K) in agreement with the thermal conductivity reported from another source.
[src:adam-style/adobe] To determine the total R-value of a wall, scale R0 by the thickness of the wall in inches.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The thermal resistance of adobe is also stated as an R-value for a 10-inch (25 cm) wall R0=4.1 hr ft2 °F/Btu.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Another source provides the following properties: conductivity 0.30 Btu/(hr ft °F) or 0.52 W/(m K); specific heat capacity 0.24 Btu/(lb °F) or 1 kJ/(kg K) and density 106 lb/cu ft (1,700 kg/m3), giving heat capacity 25.4 Btu/(ft3 °F) or 1700 kJ/(m3 K).
[src:adam-style/adobe] Using the average value of the thermal conductivity as k = 32 Btu/(hr ft °F) or 0.55 W/(m K), the thermal diffusivity is calculated to be 0.013 sq ft/h (3.4×10−7 m2/s).
[src:adam-style/adobe] Poured and puddled adobe (puddled clay, piled earth), today called *cob*, is made by placing soft adobe in layers, rather than by making individual dried bricks or using a form.
[src:adam-style/adobe] "Puddle" is a general term for a clay or clay and sand-based material worked into a dense, plastic state.
[src:adam-style/adobe] These are the oldest methods of building with adobe in the Americas until holes in the ground were used as forms, and later wooden forms used to make individual bricks were introduced by the Spanish.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Bricks made from adobe are usually made by pressing the mud mixture into an open timber frame.
[src:adam-style/adobe] In North America, the brick is typically about 25 by 36 cm (10 by 14 in) in size.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The mixture is molded into the frame, which is removed after initial setting.
[src:adam-style/adobe] After drying for a few hours, the bricks are turned on edge to finish drying.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The same mixture, without straw, is used to make mortar and often plaster on interior and exterior walls.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Some cultures used lime-based cement for the plaster to protect against rain damage.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Depending on the form into which the mixture is pressed, adobe can encompass nearly any shape or size, provided drying is even and the mixture includes reinforcement for larger bricks.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Reinforcement can include manure, straw, cement, rebar, or wooden posts.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Straw, cement, or manure added to a standard adobe mixture can produce a stronger, more crack-resistant brick.
[src:adam-style/adobe] A test is done on the soil content first.
[src:adam-style/adobe] To do so, a sample of the soil is mixed into a clear container with some water, creating an almost completely saturated liquid.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The container is shaken vigorously for one minute.
[src:adam-style/adobe] It is then allowed to settle for a day until the soil has settled into layers.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Heavier particles settle out first, sand above, silt above that, and very fine clay and organic matter will stay in suspension for days.
[src:adam-style/adobe] After the water has cleared, percentages of the various particles can be determined.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Fifty to 60 percent sand and 35 to 40 percent clay will yield strong bricks.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The Cooperative State Research, Education, and Extension Service at New Mexico State University recommends a mix of not more than 1⁄3 clay, not less than 1⁄2 sand, and never more than 1⁄3 silt.
[src:adam-style/adobe] During the Great Depression, designer and builder Hugh W.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Comstock used cheaper materials and made a specialized adobe brick called "Bitudobe." His first adobe house was built in 1936.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The ground supporting an adobe structure should be compressed, as the weight of an adobe wall is significant and foundation settling may cause cracking of the wall.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Footing depth is to be below the ground frost level.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The footing and stem wall are commonly 60 and 35 cm (24 and 14 inches) thick, respectively.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Modern construction codes call for the use of reinforcing steel in the footing and stem wall.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Adobe walls usually never rise above two stories as they are load bearing and adobe has low structural strength.
[src:adam-style/adobe] When creating window and door openings, a lintel is placed on top of the opening to support the bricks above.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Atop the last courses of brick, bond beams made of heavy wood beams or modern reinforced concrete are laid to provide a horizontal bearing plate for the roof beams and to redistribute lateral earthquake loads to shear walls more able to carry the forces.
[src:adam-style/adobe] To protect the interior and exterior adobe walls, finishes such as mud plaster, whitewash, or stucco can be applied.
[src:adam-style/adobe] These protect the adobe wall from water damage, but need to be reapplied periodically.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Alternatively, the walls can be finished with other nontraditional plasters that provide longer protection.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Bricks made with stabilized adobe generally do not need protection of plasters.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The traditional adobe roof has been constructed using a mixture of soil/clay, water, sand and organic materials.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The mixture was then formed and pressed into wood forms, producing rows of dried earth bricks that would then be laid across a support structure of wood and plastered into place with more adobe.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Depending on the materials available, a roof may be assembled using wood or metal beams to create a framework to begin layering adobe bricks.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Depending on the thickness of the adobe bricks, the framework has been preformed using a steel framing and a layering of a metal fencing or wiring over the framework to allow an even load as masses of adobe are spread across the metal fencing like cob and allowed to air dry accordingly.
[src:adam-style/adobe] This method was demonstrated with an adobe blend heavily impregnated with cement to allow even drying and prevent cracking.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The more traditional flat adobe roofs are functional only in dry climates that are not exposed to snow loads.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The heaviest wooden beams, called vigas, lie atop the wall.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Across the vigas lie smaller members called latillas and upon those brush is then laid.
[src:adam-style/adobe] To construct a flat adobe roof, beams of wood were laid to span the building, the ends of which were attached to the tops of the walls.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Once the vigas, latillas and brush are laid, adobe bricks are placed.
[src:adam-style/adobe] An adobe roof is often laid with bricks slightly larger in width to ensure a greater expanse is covered when placing the bricks onto the roof.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Following each individual brick should be a layer of adobe mortar, recommended to be at least 25 mm (1 in) thick to make certain there is ample strength between the brick's edges and also to provide a relative moisture barrier during rain.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Roof design evolved around 1850 in the American Southwest.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Three inches (8 cm) of adobe mud was applied on top of the latillas, then 18 inches (45 cm) of dry adobe dirt applied to the roof.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The dirt was contoured into a low slope to a downspout aka a 'canal'.
[src:adam-style/adobe] When moisture was applied to the roof the clay particles expanded to create a waterproof membrane.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Once a year it was necessary to pull the weeds from the roof and re-slope the dirt as needed.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Depending on the materials, adobe roofs can be inherently fire-proof.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The construction of a chimney can greatly influence the construction of the roof supports, creating an extra need for care in choosing the materials.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The builders can make an adobe chimney by stacking simple adobe bricks in a similar fashion as the surrounding walls.
[src:adam-style/adobe] In 1927, the Uniform Building Code (UBC) was adopted in the United States.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Local ordinances, referencing the UBC added requirements to building with adobe.
[src:adam-style/adobe] These included: restriction of building height of adobe structures to 1-story, requirements for adobe mix (compressive and shear strength) and new requirements which stated that every building shall be designed to withstand seismic activity, specifically lateral forces.
[src:adam-style/adobe] By the 1980s however, seismic related changes in the California Building Code effectively ended solid wall adobe construction in California; however Post-and-Beam adobe and veneers are still being used.
[src:adam-style/adobe] The largest structure ever made from adobe is the Arg-é Bam built by the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:adam-style/adobe] Other large adobe structures are the Huaca del Sol in Peru, with 100 million signed bricks and the *ciudellas* of Chan Chan and Tambo Colorado, both in Peru.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Several relatively distinct regional styles of colonial architecture are recognized in the United States.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Building styles in the 13 colonies were influenced by techniques and styles from England, as well as traditions brought by settlers from other parts of Europe.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] In New England, 17th-century colonial houses were built primarily from wood, following styles found in the southeastern counties of England.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Saltbox style homes and Cape Cod style homes were some of the simplest of homes constructed in the New England colonies.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The Saltbox homes known for their steep roof among the back the house made for easy construction among colonists.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The Cape Cod style homes were a common home in the early 17th of New England colonists, these homes featured a simple, rectangular shape commonly used by colonists.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Dutch Colonial structures, built primarily in the Hudson River Valley, Long Island, and northern New Jersey, reflected construction styles from Holland and Flanders and used stone and brick more extensively than buildings in New England.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] In Maryland, Virginia, and the Carolinas, a style called "Southern Colonial" is recognized, characterized by the hall and parlor and central-passage house types, which often had large chimneys projecting from the gable-ends of the house.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] In the Delaware Valley, Swedish colonial settlers introduced the log cabin to America.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] A style sometimes called Pennsylvania colonial appeared later (after 1681) and incorporates Georgian architectural influences.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] A Pennsylvania Dutch style is recognized in parts of southeastern Pennsylvania that were settled by German immigrants in the 18th century.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Early buildings in some other areas of the United States reflect the architectural traditions of the colonial powers that controlled these regions.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The architectural style of Louisiana is identified as French colonial, while the Spanish colonial style evokes Renaissance and Baroque styles of Spain and Mexico; in the United States it is found in Florida, Louisiana, New Mexico, Texas, Arizona, and California.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] First Period is a designation given to building styles used in the earliest English settlements at Jamestown, Virginia (1607), and Plymouth, Massachusetts (1620), and later in the other British colonies along the Eastern seaboard.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] These buildings typically included as steep roofs, small casement leaded glass windows (usually due to a scarcity of glass in the colonies), rich ornamentation (in the more expensive house only) and a massive central chimney.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Developed in French-settled areas of North America beginning with the founding of Quebec in 1608, Mobile, Alabama in 1702, and New Orleans, Louisiana, in 1718, as well as along the Mississippi River valley to Missouri.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The early French Colonial house type of the Mississippi River Valley region was the **poteaux-en-terre**, constructed of heavy upright cedar logs set vertically into the ground.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] These basic houses featured double-pitched hipped roofs and were surrounded by porches (galleries) to handle the hot summer climate.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] By 1770, the basic French Colonial house form evolved into the **briquette-entre-poteaux** (small bricks between posts) style familiar in the historic areas of New Orleans and other areas.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] These homes featured double-louvred doors, flared hip roofs, dormers, and shutters.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Developed with the earlier Spanish settlements in the Caribbean and Mexico, the Spanish Colonial style in the United States can be traced back to St.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Augustine, Florida, the oldest established city in the country, founded in 1565.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The early type of dwelling in Spanish Florida was the "board house", a small one-room cottage constructed of pit-sawn softwood boards, typically with a thatched roof.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Coquina, a limestone conglomerate containing shells of small mollusks, was used as a building stone in St.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Augustine as early as 1598 and has been used as recently as the 1930s in construction.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] There were coquina quarries on Anastasia Island.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] From these quarries, coquina was brought to build the Castillo de San Marcos, Fort Matanzas, the Cathedral Basilica, and homes throughout Florida's colonial period.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Tabby, made of lime, oyster shells, water, ash, and sand, was often poured out to make a hard flooring in these structures.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] During the 18th century, the "common houses" were whitewashed in lime mortar with an oyster shell aggregate.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Typically two-story, the houses included cooling porches to accommodate the Florida climate.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The style developed in the Southwest with Pueblo design influences from the indigenous Puebloan peoples architecture.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] In Alta California, present-day California, the style developed differently, being too far for imported building materials and without skilled builders, into a strong simple version for building the missions between 1769 and 1823.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Developed from around 1630 with the arrival of Dutch colonists to New Amsterdam and the Hudson River Valley in what is now New York and in Bergen in what is now New Jersey.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Initially the settlers built small, one room cottages with stone walls and steep roofs to allow a second floor loft.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] By 1670 or so, two-story gable-end homes were common in New Amsterdam.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] In the countryside of the Hudson Valley, the Dutch farmhouse evolved into a linear-plan home with straight-edged gables moved to the end walls.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Around 1720, the distinctive gambrel roof was adopted from the English styles, with the addition of overhangs on the front and rear to protect the mud mortar used in the typically stone walls and foundations.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Monmouth County in central New Jersey has many surviving examples of a hybrid of the Dutch style termed Anglo-Dutch colonial architecture.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Usually the earliest portions of the houses are one room and built in Dutch style with later additions built in the Georgian architecture style.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Examples being the Hankinson–Moreau–Covenhoven House, the Holmes-Hendrickson House, and many houses at Monmouth Battlefield State Park.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Developed after about 1675, when the Delaware River Valley area (Pennsylvania, New Jersey and Delaware) was settled by immigrants from Sweden, Finland, Scotland, Ireland, Germany and several other northern European nations.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The early colonists to this region adapted the "half-timber" style of construction then popular in Europe, which used a frame of braced timbers filled-in with masonry.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The "bank house" was a popular form of home during this period, typically constructed into a hillside for protection during the cold winters and hot summers of the region.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The two-story "country townhouse" was also common around Pennsylvania during this time.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The region surrounding the Chesapeake Bay on America's east coast was settled primarily by British settlers.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The standard vernacular house built by the colonists in this region between the first settlement in 1607 and the end of British rule in 1776 followed the I-plan format, had either interior or exterior gable chimneys, and was either wooden or brick.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Academic architecture was evident, but it was relatively scarce.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The best example of Mid-Atlantic Colonial academic architecture is the 1774 Hammond–Harwood House in Annapolis, Maryland.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] This house was modeled on the Villa Pisani in Montagnana, Italy, as exhibited in the Renaissance architect Andrea Palladio's Four Books of Architecture (1570).
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Colonial architect William Buckland designed this house in 1774 and the resulting house is a very skillful adaptation of the Villa Pisani for the warmer climate of the Chesapeake Bay region.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Georgian buildings, popular during the reigns of King George II and King George III were ideally built in brick, with wood trim, wooden columns and painted white.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] In what would become the United States, however, one found both brick buildings as well as those in wood with clapboards.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] They were sometimes painted a pale yellow.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] This differentiated them from most other structures that were usually not painted.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Mostly box shaped with multiple chimneys.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Georgian architecture was based on classical architecture dating to an Italian Renaissance period.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Architect Christopher Wren, who designed the Wren Building at the College of William & Mary, was a renowned Georgian architect in the colonies.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] A Georgian colonial house usually has a formally defined living room, dining room and sometimes a family room.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The bedrooms are typically on the second floor.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] They also have one or two chimneys that can be very large.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] The Georgian architectural style was most common from the early eighteenth century until the Revolutionary War, after which the American Federal style of architecture emerged.
[src:adam-style/american-colonial-architecture] Examples of remaining Georgian buildings include Gunston Hall and Hope Lodge.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] "Craftsman" was appropriated from furniture-maker Gustav Stickley, whose magazine *The Craftsman* was first published in 1901.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The architectural style was most widely used in small-to-medium-sized Southern California single-family homes from about 1905, so the smaller-scale Craftsman style became known alternatively as "California bungalow".
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The style remained popular into the 1930s and has continued with revival and restoration projects.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The American Craftsman style was a 20th century American offshoot of the British Arts and Crafts movement, which began as early as the 1860s.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Members of the Arts and Crafts movement also balked at Victorian eclecticism, which cluttered rooms with mismatched, faux-historic goods to convey a sense of worldliness.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The movement emphasized handwork over mass production.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] In some ways, it was just as much of a social movement as it was an aesthetic one, emphasizing the plight of the industrial worker and equating moral rectitude with the ability to create beautiful but simple things.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] These social currents can especially be seen in the writings of John Ruskin and William Morris, both highly influential thinkers for the movement.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] In addition, adherents sought to elevate the status of art forms that had previously been seen as a mere trade and not fine art.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The American movement also reacted against the eclectic Victorian "over-decorated" aesthetic.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The arrival of the Arts and Crafts movement in late 19th century America coincided with the decline of the Victorian era.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] American Arts and Crafts were largely based on the nature surrounding their location, they have a rustic nature to them due to materials and their design.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Gustav Stickley, in particular, hit a chord in the American populace with his goal of ennobling modest homes for a rapidly expanding American middle class, embodied in the Craftsman Bungalow style.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] American Craftsman homes still had an ornamental nature to them, the hand crafted woodwork made a statement on their own.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] In architecture, reacting to both Victorian architectural opulence and increasingly common mass-produced housing, the style incorporated a visibly sturdy structure of clean lines and natural materials.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The movement's name American Craftsman came from the popular magazine, *The Craftsman*, founded in October 1901 by philosopher, designer, furniture maker, and editor Gustav Stickley.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The magazine featured original house and furniture designs by Harvey Ellis, the Greene and Greene company, and others.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The designs, while influenced by the ideals of the British movement, found inspiration in specifically American antecedents such as Shaker furniture and the Mission Revival Style, and the Anglo-Japanese style.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Emphasis on the originality of the artist/craftsman led to the later design concepts of the 1930s Art Deco movement.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The architect and designer Frank Lloyd Wright, himself a member of the Chicago Arts and Crafts Society, was inspired by the style to become an innovator in the Prairie School of architecture and design, which shared many common goals with the Arts and Crafts movement.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The Arts and Crafts Movement emerged in the United States in Boston in the 1890s.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The area was very receptive to the ideas of the Arts and Crafts movement due to prominent thinkers like the transcendentalist Ralph Waldo Emerson and Harvard art history professor Charles Eliot Norton, who was a personal friend of British Art and Crafts leader William Morris.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The movement began with the first American Arts and Crafts Exhibition organized by the printer Henry Lewis Johnson in April 1897 at Copley Hall, featuring over 1,000 objects made by designers and craftspeople.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The exhibition's success led to the formation of the Boston Society of Arts and Crafts in June 1897 with Charles Eliot Norton as president.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The society aimed to "develop and encourage higher standards in the handicrafts." The Society focused on the relationship of artists and designers to the world of commerce and high-quality craft.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The society held its first exhibition in 1899 at Copley Hall.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] In Southern California, the Pasadena-based firm Greene and Greene was the most renowned practitioner of the original American Craftsman Style.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Their projects for Ultimate bungalows include the Gamble House and Robert R.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Blacker House in Pasadena, and the Thorsen House in Berkeley, California—with numerous others in California.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Other examples in the Los Angeles region include the Arts and Crafts Lummis House by Theodore Eisen and Sumner P.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Hunt, along the Arroyo Seco in Highland Park, California and the Journey House, located in Pasadena.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The Gamble House is considered to be the largest Craftsman style house made.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The Tifal brothers were also notable southern California American Craftsman architects, having designed more than 350 homes in Los Angeles and 100 in Monrovia in the style.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] In Northern California, architects renowned for their well-planned and detailed projects in the Craftsman style include Bernard Maybeck, with the Swedenborgian Church, and Julia Morgan, with the Asilomar Conference Grounds and Mills College projects.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Many other designers and projects represent the style in the region.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] In San Diego, California, the style was also popular.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Architect David Owen Dryden designed and built many Craftsman California bungalows in the North Park district, now a proposed Dryden Historic District.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The 1905 Marston House of George Marston in Balboa Park was designed by local architects Irving Gill and William Hebbard.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] In the early 1900s, developer Herbert J.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Hapgood built several Craftsman-style homes, many from stucco, that comprise the lakeside borough of Mountain Lakes, New Jersey.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Residents were called "Lakers." The homes followed signature styles, including bungalows and chalets.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] In Rose Valley, Pennsylvania, architect William Lightfoot Price made significant contributions to the Arts & Crafts Movement through his visionary designs and community planning.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Inspired by the movement’s ideals of craftsmanship and harmony with nature, Price transformed the former mill town into an artistic enclave, designing homes that blended organic materials, handcrafted details, and a commitment to aesthetic simplicity.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] His work in Rose Valley, including its thoughtfully designed cottages and communal spaces, embodied the movement’s philosophy of integrating art into everyday life, making it a lasting example of the Arts & Crafts ideal in America.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] The Castle in the Clouds, a mountaintop estate built in the Ossipee Mountains of New Hampshire in 1913–1914 for Thomas Gustave Plant by architect J.
[src:adam-style/american-craftsman] Williams Beal, is an example of the American Craftsman style in New England.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] The **American Foursquare** (also **American Four Square** or **American 4 Square**) is an American house vernacular under the Arts and Crafts style popular from the mid-1890s to the late 1930s.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] A reaction to the ornate and mass-produced elements of the Victorian and other Revival styles popular throughout the last half of the 19th century, the American Foursquare was plain, often incorporating handcrafted "honest" woodwork (unless purchased from a mail-order catalog).
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] This architectural vernacular incorporates elements of the Prairie School and the Craftsman styles.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] It is also sometimes called Transitional Period.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] The hallmarks of the vernacular include a basically square, boxy design, two-and-one-half stories high, usually with four large, boxy rooms to a floor (with the exception of the attic floor, which typically has only one or two rooms), a center dormer, and a large front porch with wide stairs.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] The boxy shape provides a maximum amount of interior room space, to use a small city lot to best advantage.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] Other common features included a hipped roof, arched entries between common rooms, built-in cabinetry, and Craftsman-style woodwork.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] A typical design would be as follows: first floor, from front to back, on one side, the living room and dining room; while on the other side, the entry room or foyer, stairway and kitchen.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] Second floor, front to back, on one side, bedroom, bathroom and bedroom; while on the other side, bedroom, stairway and bedroom.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] The upstairs bathroom would generally be placed above the kitchen, so that the plumbing could run directly from one to the other.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] The bedrooms had a slightly longer dimension along the front and back of the house with side-by-side closets between the bedrooms.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] This gave a very efficient layout, with a bedroom in each corner and a centralized bathroom and stairway.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] The top floor was generally just a big open space with one to four dormers, essentially an attic, whether finished into living space or not.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] The basement generally contained a large natural convection furnace or boiler, exhausting to a chimney running upwards through the center of the house, which also provided exhaust for the stove.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] Foursquare houses may be built with a variety of materials, including bricks and wood frames.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] Later models include built-in shelves and other amenities.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] Large tracts of these homes exist in older Midwestern urban neighborhoods, particularly streetcar suburbs, but the design was used everywhere.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] As with other styles in streetcar suburbs, it was tailored to relatively narrow lots, and was multi-story, allowing more square footage on a smaller footprint.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] The American Foursquare style is occasionally revived in new developments, although its appeal is as a "traditional-looking" style rather than a fully authentic one, often including modern two-car attached garages and other features absent in originals, and typically built on larger lots.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] The American Foursquare or "Prairie Box" was a post-Victorian style, which shared many features with the Prairie architecture pioneered by Frank Lloyd Wright.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] During the early 1900s and 1910s, Wright even designed his own variations on the Foursquare, including the Robert M.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] Lamp House, "A Fireproof House for $5000", and several two-story models for American System-Built Homes.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] Unlike other houses of the style, Wright's versions featured more open main floor plans achieved by removing or minimizing partitions between the entry, living room, and dining room.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] He in turn inspired other Prairie School architects, such as Walter Burley Griffin, to design similar Foursquares in the following decades.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] Other variations on the American Foursquare emerged regionally during the first decades of the 20th century.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] In Kansas City, the Shirtwaist-style emerged, with a brick or limestone first floor and siding-wrapped second and third floors.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] The style is named for the higher-waisted women's fashion of the time.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] Later Foursquares often had the same type of interiors as bungalows, with open floor plans, many built-ins, and fireplaces.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] Many examples are trimmed with tiled roofs, cornice-line brackets, or other details drawn from Craftsman, Italian Renaissance, or Mission architecture.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] The Foursquare was a popular mail-order era style along with the California bungalow.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] When one was ordered, it came in a boxcar with a book of directions and all the parts pre-cut and numbered for self-assembly.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] These homes are particularly common in neighborhoods near rail-lines built in this era.
[src:adam-style/american-foursquare] The largest mail-order house catalog companies were Sears and Aladdin.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] The **American Renaissance** was a period of American architecture and the arts from 1876 to 1917, characterized by renewed national self-confidence and a feeling that the United States was the heir to Greek democracy, Roman law, and Renaissance humanism.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] Local conditions and requirements of America, including the aforementioned nationalism, spurred this change of style, allowing it to slowly develop over time in various places around the United States.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] The era spans the period between the Centennial Exposition (celebrating the 100th anniversary of the signing of the Declaration of Independence) and the United States' entry into World War I.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] A great variety of buildings were made using this style, such as townhouses, cottages, state houses, libraries, capitol buildings, museums, banks, railway terminals, and more.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] Early buildings of the American Renaissance were of wood, plentiful in the United States, and often painted.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] As the country became wealthier, builders gradually followed the Greeks and Romans in their use of stone.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] For example, early columns of the period were carved of wood, but later architects and builders could use white marble, a more durable material, for intricate carvings and details.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] Wood is more easily repaired and replaced given its lack of lengthy durability in addition to its charm, warmth, and personality, which is characteristic of the American style.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] Stone, especially white marble, has a shine and glow to it.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] It is also more durable and able to withstand harsh weather.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] Decorative elements, such as arches, domes, vaulted ceilings, and columns were commonplace during the American Renaissance.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] There was a strong desire for the revival of Classical forms, symmetrical designs, and elaborate decorative elements.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] A sense of national identity was created and explored through the use of local materials and motifs.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] During the American Renaissance, the United States' preoccupation with national identity (or New Nationalism) was expressed by modernism and technology, as well as academic classicism.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] This classicism made way for a new form of creative and artistic rhetoric, which in turn helped establish the new aesthetic of the time.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] It expressed its self-confidence in new technologies, such as the wire cables of the Brooklyn Bridge in New York City.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] It found its cultural outlets in Prairie School houses and in Beaux-Arts architecture and sculpture, in the "City Beautiful" movement, and in the creation of the American empire.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] A goal of the "City Beautiful" movement, which coincides with the American Renaissance, was, "to shape American culture and society aesthetically, morally, and professionally".
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] Through this goal, order, acculturation, and assimilation were meant to be brought to the American city, easing the transition for immigrants while also establishing a professional authority through architecture.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] Americans felt that their civilization was uniquely the modern heir, and that it had come of age.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] Politically and economically, this era coincides with the Gilded Age and the New Imperialism.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] At McKim's death in 1909, his architectural firm was the largest in the world, having produced nearly 900 buildings of Classical orders and finely proportioned masonry.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] The theme is followed by Edwin Blashfield's mural *The Evolution of Civilization* in the dome of the reading room at the new Library of Congress.
[src:adam-style/american-renaissance] The 1979 exhibition *American Renaissance: 1876–1917* at the Brooklyn Museum helped revive interest in the movement.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The conflict was fought in North America, the Caribbean, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The war's outcome seemed uncertain for most of the war, but Washington and the Continental Army's decisive victory in the Siege of Yorktown in 1781 led King George III and the Kingdom of Great Britain to negotiate an end to the war.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In 1783, in the Treaty of Paris, the British monarchy acknowledged the independence of the Thirteen Colonies, leading to the establishment of the United States as an independent and sovereign nation.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In 1763, after the British Empire gained dominance in North America following its victory over the French in the Seven Years' War, tensions and disputes began escalating between the British and the Thirteen Colonies, especially following passage of the Stamp and Townshend Acts.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The British Army responded by seeking to occupy Boston militarily, leading to the Boston Massacre on March 5, 1770.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In mid-1774, with tensions escalating even further between the British Army and the colonies, the British Parliament imposed the Intolerable Acts, an attempt to disarm Americans, leading to the Battles of Lexington and Concord in April 1775, the first battles of the Revolutionary War.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In June 1775, the Second Continental Congress voted to incorporate colonial-based Patriot militias into a central military, the Continental Army, and unanimously appointed Washington its commander-in-chief.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Two months later, in August 1775, George III declared the colonies to be in a state of rebellion.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In July 1776, the Second Continental Congress formalized the war, passing the Lee Resolution on July 2, and, two days later, unanimously adopting the Declaration of Independence, on July 4.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In March 1776, in an early win for the newly-formed Continental Army under Washington's command, following a successful siege of Boston, the Continental Army successfully drove the British Army out of Boston.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] British commander in chief William Howe responded by launching the New York and New Jersey campaign, which resulted in Howe's capture of New York City in November.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Washington responded by clandestinely crossing the Delaware River and winning small but significant victories at Trenton and Princeton.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In the summer of 1777, as Howe was poised to capture Philadelphia, the Continental Congress fled to Baltimore.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In October 1777, a separate northern British force under the command of John Burgoyne was forced to surrender at Saratoga in an American victory that proved crucial in convincing France and Spain that an independent United States was a viable possibility.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] France signed a commercial agreement with the revolutionaires, followed by a Treaty of Alliance in February 1778.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In 1779, the Sullivan Expedition undertook a scorched earth campaign against British-allied factions of the Haudenosaunee Confederacy (*also* Iroquois).
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Native American raids on the American frontier, however, continued to be a problem.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Also, in 1779, Spain allied with France against Great Britain in the Treaty of Aranjuez, though Spain did not formally ally with the Americans.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Howe's replacement Henry Clinton intended to take the war against the Americans into the Southern Colonies.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Despite some initial success, British General Cornwallis was besieged by a Franco-American army in Yorktown, Virginia, in September and October 1781.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The French navy cut off Cornwallis's escape and he was forced to surrender in October.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The British wars with France and Spain continued for another two years, but fighting largely ceased in North America.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In the Treaty of Paris, signed on September 3, 1783, Great Britain acknowledged the sovereignty and independence of the United States, bringing the American Revolutionary War to an end.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Treaties of Versailles resolved Great Britain's conflicts with France and Spain, and forced Great Britain to cede Tobago, Senegal, and small territories in India to France, and Menorca, West Florida, and East Florida to Spain.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The French and Indian War, part of the wider global conflict known as the Seven Years' War, ended with the 1763 Peace of Paris, which expelled France from their possessions in New France.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Royal Proclamation of 1763 was designed to refocus colonial expansion north into Nova Scotia and south into Florida, with the Mississippi River as the dividing line between British and Spanish possessions in America.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Settlement was tightly restricted beyond the 1763 limits, and claims west of this line, including by Virginia and Massachusetts, were rescinded.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] With the exception of Virginia and others deprived of rights to western lands, the colonial legislatures agreed on the boundaries but disagreed on where to set them.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Many settlers resented the restrictions entirely, and enforcement required permanent garrisons along the frontier, which led to increasingly bitter disputes over who should pay for them.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The huge debt incurred by the Seven Years' War and demands from British taxpayers for cuts in government expenditure meant Parliament expected the colonies to fund their own defense.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The 1763 to 1765 Grenville ministry instructed the Royal Navy to cease trading smuggled goods and enforce customs duties levied in American ports.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The most important was the 1733 Molasses Act; routinely ignored before 1763, it had a significant economic impact since 85% of New England rum exports were manufactured from imported molasses.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] These measures were followed by the Sugar Act and Stamp Act, which imposed additional taxes on the colonies to pay for defending the western frontier.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The taxes proved highly burdensome, particularly for the poorer classes, and quickly became a source of discontent.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In July 1765, the Whigs formed the First Rockingham ministry, which repealed the Stamp Act and reduced tax on foreign molasses to help the New England economy, but re-asserted Parliamentary authority in the Declaratory Act.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, this did little to end the discontent; in 1768, a riot started in Boston when the authorities seized the sloop *Liberty* on suspicion of smuggling.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Tensions escalated in March 1770 when British troops fired on rock-throwing civilians, killing five in what became known as the Boston Massacre.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Massacre coincided with the partial repeal of the Townshend Acts by the Tory-based North Ministry.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] North insisted on retaining duty on tea to enshrine Parliament's right to tax the colonies; the amount was minor, but ignored the fact it was that very principle Americans found objectionable.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In April 1772, colonialists staged the first American tax revolt against British royal authority in Weare, New Hampshire, later referred to as the Pine Tree Riot.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] This would inspire the design of the Pine Tree Flag.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Tensions escalated following the destruction of a customs vessel in the June 1772 Gaspee Affair, then came to a head in 1773.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] A banking crisis led to the near-collapse of the East India Company, which dominated the British economy; to support it, Parliament passed the Tea Act, giving it a trading monopoly in the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Since most American tea was smuggled by the Dutch, the act was opposed by those who managed the illegal trade, while being seen as another attempt to impose the principle of taxation by Parliament.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In December 1773, a group called the Sons of Liberty disguised as Mohawks dumped crates of tea into Boston Harbor, an event later known as the Boston Tea Party.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The British Parliament responded by passing the so-called Intolerable Acts, aimed specifically at Massachusetts, although many colonists and members of the Whig opposition considered them a threat to liberty in general.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] This increased sympathy for the Patriot cause locally, in the British Parliament, and in the London press.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Throughout the 18th century, the elected lower houses in the colonial legislatures gradually wrested power from their governors.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Dominated by smaller landowners and merchants, these assemblies now established ad-hoc provincial legislatures, effectively replacing royal control.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] With the exception of Georgia, twelve colonies sent representatives to the First Continental Congress to agree on a unified response to the crisis.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Many of the delegates feared that a boycott would result in war and sent a Petition to the King calling for the repeal of the Intolerable Acts.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] After some debate, on September 17, 1774, Congress endorsed the Massachusetts Suffolk Resolves and on October 20 passed the Continental Association, which instituted economic sanctions and a boycott of goods against Britain.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] While denying its authority over internal American affairs, a faction led by James Duane and future Loyalist Joseph Galloway insisted Congress recognize Parliament's right to regulate colonial trade.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Expecting concessions by the North administration, Congress authorized the colonial legislatures to enforce the boycott; this succeeded in reducing British imports by 97% from 1774 to 1775.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, on February 9 Parliament declared Massachusetts to be in rebellion and instituted a blockade of the colony.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In July, the Restraining Acts limited colonial trade with the British West Indies and Britain and barred New England ships from the Newfoundland cod fisheries.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The tension led to a scramble for control of militia stores, which each assembly was legally obliged to maintain for defense.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] On April 19, a British attempt to secure the Concord arsenal culminated in the Battles of Lexington and Concord, which began the Revolutionary War.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] After the Patriot victory at Concord, moderates in Congress led by John Dickinson drafted the Olive Branch Petition, offering to accept royal authority in return for George III mediating in the dispute.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, since the petition was immediately followed by the Declaration of the Causes and Necessity of Taking Up Arms, Colonial Secretary Lord Dartmouth viewed the offer as insincere and refused to present the petition to the king.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Although constitutionally correct, since the monarch could not oppose his own government, it disappointed those Americans who hoped he would mediate in the dispute, while the hostility of his language annoyed even Loyalist members of Congress.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Combined with the Proclamation of Rebellion, issued on August 23 in response to the Battle at Bunker Hill, it ended hopes of a peaceful settlement.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Backed by the Whigs, Parliament initially rejected the imposition of coercive measures by 170 votes, fearing an aggressive policy would drive the Americans towards independence.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, by the end of 1774 the collapse of British authority meant both Lord North and George III were convinced war was inevitable.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] After Boston, Gage halted operations and awaited reinforcements; the Irish Parliament approved the recruitment of new regiments, while allowing Catholics to enlist for the first time.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Britain also signed a series of treaties with German states to supply additional troops.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Within a year, it had an army of over 32,000 men in America, the largest ever sent outside Europe at the time.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The employment of German soldiers against people viewed as British citizens was opposed by many in Parliament and by the colonial assemblies; combined with the lack of activity by Gage, opposition to the use of foreign troops allowed the Patriots to take control of the legislatures.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Support for independence was boosted by Thomas Paine's pamphlet *Common Sense*, which was published on January 10, 1776, and argued for American self-government and was widely reprinted.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] To draft the Declaration of Independence, the Second Continental Congress appointed the Committee of Five: Thomas Jefferson, John Adams, Benjamin Franklin, Roger Sherman, and Robert Livingston.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The declaration was written almost exclusively by Jefferson.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Identifying inhabitants of the Thirteen Colonies as "one people", the declaration simultaneously dissolved political links with Britain, while including a long list of alleged violations of "English rights" committed by George III.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] This is also one of the first times that the colonies were referred to as "United States", rather than the more common United Colonies.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] On July 2, Congress voted for independence and published the declaration on July 4.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] At this point, the revolution ceased to be an internal dispute over trade and tax policies between the Thirteen Colonies and Great Britain, becoming a civil war, with each state represented in Congress engaged in a struggle with Britain.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The conflict was also a civil war between American Patriots and American Loyalists.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Patriots generally supported independence from Britain and a new national union in Congress, while Loyalists remained aligned with British rule.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Estimates of numbers vary, one suggestion being the population as a whole was split evenly between committed Patriots, committed Loyalists, and those who were indifferent.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Others calculate the split as 40% Patriot, 40% neutral, 20% Loyalist, but with considerable regional variations.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] At the onset of the war, the Second Continental Congress realized defeating Britain required foreign alliances and intelligence-gathering.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Committee of Secret Correspondence was formed for "the sole purpose of corresponding with our friends in Great Britain and other parts of the world".
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] From 1775 to 1776, the committee shared information and built alliances through secret correspondence, as well as employing secret agents in Europe to gather intelligence, conduct undercover operations, analyze foreign publications, and initiate Patriot propaganda campaigns.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Paine served as secretary, while Benjamin Franklin and Silas Deane, sent to France, Britain's longtime rival, to recruit military engineers, were instrumental in securing French aid in Paris.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On April 14, 1775, Sir Thomas Gage, Commander-in-Chief, North America and Governor of Massachusetts, received orders to take action against the Patriots.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He decided to destroy militia ordnance stored at Concord, Massachusetts, and capture John Hancock and Samuel Adams, who were considered the principal instigators of the rebellion.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The operation was to begin around midnight on April 19, in the hope of completing it before the American Patriots could respond.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, Paul Revere learned of the plan and notified Captain Parker, commander of the Concord militia, who prepared to resist.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The first action of the war, commonly referred to as the shot heard round the world, was a brief skirmish at Lexington, followed by the full-scale Battles of Lexington and Concord.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British troops suffered around 300 casualties before withdrawing to Boston, which was then besieged by the militia.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In May 1775, 4,500 British reinforcements arrived under Generals William Howe, John Burgoyne, and Sir Henry Clinton.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 17, they seized the Charlestown Peninsula at the Battle of Bunker Hill, a frontal assault in which they suffered over 1,000 casualties.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Dismayed at the costly attack which had gained them little, Gage appealed to London for a larger army, but instead was replaced as commander by Howe.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 14, 1775, Congress took control of Patriot forces outside Boston, and Congressional leader John Adams nominated Washington as commander-in-chief of the newly formed Continental Army.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 16, Hancock officially proclaimed him "General and Commander in Chief of the army of the United Colonies." He assumed command on July 3, preferring to fortify Dorchester Heights outside Boston rather than assaulting it.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In early March 1776, Colonel Henry Knox arrived with heavy artillery acquired in the Capture of Fort Ticonderoga.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Under cover of darkness, on March 5, Washington placed these on Dorchester Heights, from where they could fire on the town and British ships in Boston Harbor.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Fearing another Bunker Hill, Howe evacuated the city on March 17 without further loss and sailed to Halifax, Nova Scotia, while Washington moved south to New York City.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Beginning in August 1775, American privateers raided towns in Nova Scotia, including Saint John, Charlottetown, and Yarmouth.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In 1776, John Paul Jones and Jonathan Eddy attacked Canso and Fort Cumberland respectively.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British officials in Quebec began negotiating with the Iroquois for their support, while US envoys urged them to remain neutral.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Aware of Native American leanings toward the British and fearing an Anglo-Indian attack from Canada, Congress authorized a second invasion in April 1775.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After the defeat at the Battle of Quebec on December 31, the Americans maintained a loose blockade of the city until they retreated on May 6, 1776.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A second defeat at Trois-Rivières on June 8 ended operations in Quebec.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British pursuit was initially blocked by American naval vessels on Lake Champlain until victory at Valcour Island on October 11 forced the Americans to withdraw to Fort Ticonderoga, while in December an uprising in Nova Scotia sponsored by Massachusetts was defeated at Fort Cumberland.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] These failures impacted public support for the Patriot cause, and aggressive anti-Loyalist policies in the New England colonies alienated the Canadians.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In Virginia, Dunmore's Proclamation on November 7, 1775, promised freedom to any slaves who fled their Patriot masters and agreed to fight for the Crown.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British forces were defeated at Great Bridge on December 9 and took refuge on British ships anchored near Norfolk.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When the Third Virginia Convention refused to disband its militia or accept martial law, Lord Dunmore ordered the Burning of Norfolk on January 1, 1776.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The siege of Savage's Old Fields began on November 19 in South Carolina between Loyalist and Patriot militias, and the Loyalists were subsequently driven out of the colony in the Snow Campaign.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Loyalists were recruited in North Carolina to reassert British rule in the South, but they were decisively defeated in the Battle of Moore's Creek Bridge.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A British expedition sent to reconquer South Carolina launched an attack on Charleston in the Battle of Sullivan's Island on June 28, 1776, but it failed.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A shortage of gunpowder led Congress to authorize a naval expedition against the Bahamas to secure ordnance stored there.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On March 3, 1776, an American squadron under the command of Esek Hopkins landed at the east end of Nassau and encountered minimal resistance at Fort Montagu.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Hopkins' troops then marched on Fort Nassau.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Hopkins had promised governor Montfort Browne and the civilian inhabitants that their lives and property would not be in any danger if they offered no resistance; they complied.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Hopkins captured large stores of powder and other munitions that was so great he had to impress an extra ship in the harbor to transport the supplies back home, when he departed on March 17.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A month later, after a brief skirmish with HMS *Glasgow*, they returned to New London, Connecticut, the base for American naval operations.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After regrouping at Halifax in Nova Scotia, Howe set sail for New York in June 1776 and began landing troops on Staten Island near the entrance to New York Harbor on July 2.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Americans rejected Howe's informal attempt to negotiate peace on July 30; Washington knew that an attack on the city was imminent and realized that he needed advance information to deal with disciplined British regular troops.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On August 12, 1776, Patriot Thomas Knowlton was ordered to form an elite group for reconnaissance and secret missions.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Knowlton's Rangers, which included Nathan Hale, became the Army's first intelligence unit.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Washington was driven off Long Island, he soon realized that he would need to professionalize military intelligence.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] With aid from Benjamin Tallmadge, Washington launched the six-man Culper spy ring.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The efforts of Washington and the Culper Spy Ring substantially increased the effective allocation and deployment of Continental regiments in the field.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Throughout the war, Washington spent more than 10 percent of his total military funds on military intelligence.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington split the Continental Army into positions on Manhattan and across the East River in western Long Island.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On August 27 at the Battle of Long Island, Howe outflanked Washington and forced him back to Brooklyn Heights, but he did not attempt to encircle Washington's forces.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Through the night of August 28, Knox bombarded the British.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Knowing they were up against overwhelming odds, Washington ordered the assembly of a war council on August 29; all agreed to retreat to Manhattan.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington quickly had his troops assembled and ferried them across the East River to Manhattan on flat-bottomed freight boats without any losses in men or ordnance, leaving General Thomas Mifflin's regiments as a rearguard.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Howe met with a delegation from the Second Continental Congress at the September Staten Island Peace Conference, but it failed to conclude peace, largely because the British delegates only had the authority to offer pardons and could not recognize independence.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On September 15, Howe seized control of New York City when the British landed at Kip's Bay and unsuccessfully engaged the Americans at the Battle of Harlem Heights the following day.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On October 18, Howe failed to encircle the Americans at the Battle of Pell's Point, and the Americans withdrew.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Howe declined to close with Washington's army on October 28 at the Battle of White Plains and instead attacked a hill that was of no strategic value.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington's retreat isolated his remaining forces and the British captured Fort Washington on November 16.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British victory there amounted to Washington's most disastrous defeat with the loss of 3,000 prisoners.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The remaining American regiments on Long Island fell back four days later.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] General Henry Clinton wanted to pursue Washington's disorganized army, but he was first required to commit 6,000 troops to capture Newport, Rhode Island, to secure the Loyalist port.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] General Charles Cornwallis pursued Washington, but Howe ordered him to halt.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The outlook following the defeat at Fort Washington appeared bleak for the American cause.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The reduced Continental Army had dwindled to fewer than 5,000 men and was reduced further when enlistments expired at the end of the year.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Popular support wavered, and morale declined.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On December 20, 1776, the Continental Congress abandoned the revolutionary capital of Philadelphia and moved to Baltimore, where it remained until February 27, 1777.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Loyalist activity surged in the wake of the American defeat, especially in New York state.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In London, news of the victorious Long Island campaign was well received with festivities held in the capital.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Strategic deficiencies among Patriot forces were evident: Washington divided a numerically weaker army in the face of a stronger one, his inexperienced staff misread the military situation, and American troops fled in the face of enemy fire.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The successes led to predictions that the British could win within a year.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British established winter quarters in the New York City area and anticipated renewed campaigning the following spring.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On the night of December 25–26, 1776, Washington crossed the Delaware River, leading a column of Continental Army troops from today's Bucks County, Pennsylvania, to today's Mercer County, New Jersey, in a logistically challenging and dangerous operation.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Meanwhile, the Hessians were involved in numerous clashes with small bands of Patriots and were often aroused by false alarms at night in the weeks before the actual Battle of Trenton.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] By Christmas they were tired, while a heavy snowstorm led their commander, Colonel Johann Rall, to assume no significant attack would occur.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] At daybreak on the 26th, the American Patriots surprised and overwhelmed Rall and his troops, who lost over 20 killed including Rall, while 900 prisoners, German cannons and supplies were captured.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Battle of Trenton restored the American army's morale, reinvigorated the Patriot cause, and dispelled their fear of what they regarded as Hessian "mercenaries".
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A British attempt to retake Trenton was repulsed at Assunpink Creek on January 2; during the night, Washington outmaneuvered Cornwallis, then defeated his rearguard in the Battle of Princeton the following day.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The two victories helped convince the French that the Americans were worthy military allies.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After his success at Princeton, Washington entered winter quarters at Morristown, New Jersey, where he remained until May and received Congressional direction to inoculate all Patriot troops against smallpox.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] With the exception of a minor skirmishing between the two armies which continued until March, Howe made no attempt to attack the Americans.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The 1776 campaign demonstrated that regaining New England would be a prolonged affair, which led to a change in British strategy to isolating the north by taking control of the Hudson River, allowing them to focus on the south where Loyalist support was believed to be substantial.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In December 1776, Howe wrote to the Colonial Secretary Lord Germain, proposing a limited offensive against Philadelphia, while a second force moved down the Hudson from Canada.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Burgoyne supplied several alternatives, all of which gave him responsibility for the offensive, with Howe remaining on the defensive.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The option selected required him to lead the main force south from Montreal down the Hudson Valley, while a detachment under Barry St.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The two would meet at Albany, leaving Howe to decide whether to join them.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Reasonable in principle, this did not account for the logistical difficulties involved and Burgoyne erroneously assumed Howe would remain on the defensive; Germain's failure to make this clear meant he opted to attack Philadelphia instead.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] With a mixed force of British regulars, professional German soldiers and Canadian militia Burgoyne set out on June 14, 1777, and captured Fort Ticonderoga on July 5.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As General Horatio Gates retreated, his troops blocked roads, destroyed bridges, dammed streams, and stripped the area of food.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This slowed Burgoyne's progress and forced him to send out large foraging expeditions; one of more than 700 British troops were captured at the Battle of Bennington on August 16.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] St Leger moved east and besieged Fort Stanwix; despite defeating an American relief force at the Battle of Oriskany on August 6, St.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Leger was abandoned by his Indian allies and withdrew to Quebec on August 22.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Now isolated and outnumbered by Gates, Burgoyne continued onto Albany rather than retreating to Fort Ticonderoga, reaching Saratoga on September 13.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He asked Clinton for support while constructing defenses around the town.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Morale among his troops rapidly declined, and an unsuccessful attempt to break past Gates at the Battle of Freeman Farms on September 19 resulted in 600 British casualties.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Clinton advised he could not reach them, Burgoyne's subordinates advised retreat; a reconnaissance in force on October 7 was repulsed by Gates at the Battle of Bemis Heights, forcing them back into Saratoga with heavy losses.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] By October 11, all hope of British escape had vanished; persistent rain reduced the camp to a "squalid hell" and supplies were dangerously low.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Burgoyne capitulated on October 17; around 6,222 soldiers, including German forces commanded by General Friedrich Adolf Riedesel, surrendered their arms before being taken to Boston, where they were to be transported to England.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After securing additional supplies, Howe made another attempt on Philadelphia by landing his troops in Chesapeake Bay on August 24.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He now compounded failure to support Burgoyne by missing repeated opportunities to destroy his opponent: despite defeating Washington at the Battle of Brandywine on September 11, he then allowed him to withdraw in good order.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After dispersing an American detachment at Paoli on September 20, Cornwallis occupied Philadelphia on September 26, with the main force of 9,000 under Howe based just to the north at Germantown.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington attacked them on October 4, but was repulsed.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] To prevent Howe's forces in Philadelphia being resupplied by sea, the Patriots erected Fort Mifflin and nearby Fort Mercer on the east and west banks of the Delaware respectively, and placed obstacles in the river south of the city.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This was supported by a small flotilla of Continental Navy ships on the Delaware, supplemented by the Pennsylvania State Navy, commanded by John Hazelwood.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] An attempt by the Royal Navy to take the forts in the October 20 to 22 Battle of Red Bank failed; a second attack captured Fort Mifflin on November 16, while Fort Mercer was abandoned two days later when Cornwallis breached the walls.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] His supply lines secured, Howe tried to tempt Washington into giving battle, but after inconclusive skirmishing at the Battle of White Marsh from December 5 to 8, he withdrew to Philadelphia for the winter.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On December 19, the Americans followed suit and entered winter quarters at Valley Forge.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As Washington's domestic opponents contrasted his lack of battlefield success with Gates' victory at Saratoga, foreign observers such as Frederick the Great were equally impressed with Washington's command at Germantown, which demonstrated resilience and determination.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Over the winter, poor conditions, supply problems and low morale resulted in 2,000 deaths, with another 3,000 unfit for duty due to lack of shoes.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, Baron Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben took the opportunity to introduce Prussian Army drill and infantry tactics to "model companies" in each Continental Army regiment, who then instructed their home units.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite Valley Forge being only twenty miles away, Howe made no effort to attack their camp, an action some critics argue could have ended the war.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Like his predecessors, French foreign minister Vergennes considered the 1763 Peace a national humiliation and viewed the war as an opportunity to weaken Britain.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He initially avoided open conflict, but allowed American ships to take on cargoes in French ports, a technical violation of neutrality.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Vergennes persuaded Louis XVI to secretly fund a government front company to purchase munitions for the Patriots, carried in neutral Dutch ships and imported through Sint Eustatius in the Caribbean.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Many Americans opposed a French alliance, fearing to "exchange one tyranny for another", but this changed after a series of military setbacks in early 1776.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As France had nothing to gain from the colonies reconciling with Britain, Congress had three choices: making peace on British terms, continuing the struggle on their own, or proclaiming independence, guaranteed by France.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although the Declaration of Independence had wide public support, over 20% of Congressmen voted against an alliance with France.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Congress agreed to the treaty with reluctance and as the war moved in their favor increasingly lost interest in it.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Silas Deane was sent to Paris to begin negotiations with Vergennes, whose key objectives were replacing Britain as the United States' primary commercial and military partner while securing the French West Indies from American expansion.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] These islands were extremely valuable; in 1772, the value of sugar and coffee produced by Saint-Domingue on its own exceeded that of all American exports combined.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Talks progressed slowly until October 1777, when British defeat at Saratoga and their apparent willingness to negotiate peace convinced Vergennes only a permanent alliance could prevent the "disaster" of Anglo-American rapprochement.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Assurances of formal French support allowed Congress to reject the Carlisle Peace Commission and insist on nothing short of complete independence.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On February 6, 1778, France and the United States signed the Treaty of Amity and Commerce regulating trade between the two countries, followed by a defensive military alliance against Britain, the Treaty of Alliance.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In return for French guarantees of American independence, Congress undertook to defend their interests in the West Indies, while both sides agreed not to make a separate peace; conflict over these provisions would lead to the 1798 to 1800 Quasi-War.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Charles III of Spain was invited to join on the same terms but refused, largely due to concerns over the impact of the Revolution on Spanish colonies in the Americas.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Spain had complained on multiple occasions about encroachment by American settlers into Louisiana, a problem that could only get worse once the United States replaced Britain.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although Spain ultimately made important contributions to American success, in the Treaty of Aranjuez, Charles agreed only to support France's war with Britain outside America, in return for help in recovering Gibraltar, Menorca and Spanish Florida.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The terms were confidential since several conflicted with American aims; for example, the French claimed exclusive control of the Newfoundland cod fisheries, a non-negotiable for colonies like Massachusetts.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] One less well-known impact of this agreement was the abiding American distrust of 'foreign entanglements'; the US would not sign another treaty with France until their NATO agreement of 1949.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This was because the US had agreed not to make peace without France, while Aranjuez committed France to keep fighting until Spain recovered Gibraltar, effectively making it a condition of US independence without the knowledge of Congress.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] To encourage French participation in the struggle for independence, the US representative in Paris, Silas Deane, promised promotion and command positions to any French officer who joined the Continental Army.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This included Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette, whom Congress via Dean appointed a major general, on July 31, 1777.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When the war started, Britain tried to borrow the Dutch-based Scots Brigade for service in America, but pro-Patriot sentiment led the States General to refuse.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although the Republic was no longer a major power, prior to 1774 they still dominated the European carrying trade, and Dutch merchants made large profits shipping French-supplied munitions to the Patriots.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This ended when Britain declared war in December 1780, a conflict that proved disastrous to the Dutch economy.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British government failed to take into account the strength of the American merchant marine and support from European countries, which allowed the colonies to import munitions and continue trading with relative impunity.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] While well aware of this, the North administration delayed placing the Royal Navy on a war footing for cost reasons; this prevented the institution of an effective blockade.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Traditional British policy was to employ European land-based allies to divert the opposition; in 1778, they were diplomatically isolated and faced war on multiple fronts.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Meanwhile, George III had given up on subduing America while Britain had a European war to fight.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He did not welcome war with France, but he held the British victories over France in the Seven Years' War as a reason to believe in ultimate victory over France.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Britain subsequently changed its focus into the Caribbean theater, and diverted major military resources away from America.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] At the end of 1777, Howe resigned and was replaced by Sir Henry Clinton on May 24, 1778; with French entry into the war, he was ordered to consolidate his forces in New York.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 18, the British departed Philadelphia with the reinvigorated Americans in pursuit; the Battle of Monmouth on June 28 was inconclusive but boosted Patriot morale.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] That midnight, the newly installed Clinton continued his retreat to New York.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A French naval force under Admiral Charles Henri Hector d'Estaing was sent to assist Washington; deciding New York was too formidable a target, in August they launched a combined attack on Newport, with General John Sullivan commanding land forces.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The resulting Battle of Rhode Island was indecisive; badly damaged by a storm, the French withdrew to avoid risking their ships.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Further activity was limited to British raids on Chestnut Neck and Little Egg Harbor in October.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In July 1779, the Americans captured British positions at Stony Point and Paulus Hook.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton unsuccessfully tried to tempt Washington into a decisive engagement by sending General William Tryon to raid Connecticut.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In July, a large American naval operation, the Penobscot Expedition, attempted to retake Maine but was defeated.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Persistent raids by British-allied tribes in New York and Pennsylvania led to the punitive Sullivan Expedition from July to September 1779.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, 5,000 British-allied tribes of Iroquois fled to Canada where, supplied and supported by the British, they continued their raids.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] During the winter of 1779–1780, the Continental Army suffered greater hardships than at Valley Forge.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Morale was poor, public support fell away, the Continental dollar was virtually worthless, the army was plagued with supply problems, desertion was common, and mutinies occurred in the Pennsylvania Line and New Jersey Line regiments over the conditions.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In June 1780, Clinton sent 6,000 men under Wilhelm von Knyphausen to retake New Jersey, but they were halted by local militia at the Battle of Connecticut Farms; although the Americans withdrew, Knyphausen felt he was not strong enough to engage Washington's main force and retreated.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A second attempt two weeks later ended in a British defeat at the Battle of Springfield, effectively ending their ambitions in New Jersey.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In July, Washington appointed Benedict Arnold commander of West Point; his attempt to betray the fort to the British failed due to incompetent planning, and the plot was revealed when his British contact John André was captured and executed.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Arnold escaped to New York and switched sides, an action justified in a pamphlet addressed "To the Inhabitants of America"; the Patriots condemned his betrayal, while he found himself almost as unpopular with the British.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Southern Strategy was developed by Lord Germain, based on input from London-based Loyalists, including Joseph Galloway.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] They argued that it made no sense to fight the Patriots in the north where they were strongest, while the New England economy was reliant on trade with Britain.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On the other hand, duties on tobacco made the South far more profitable for Britain, while local support meant securing it required small numbers of regular troops.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Victory would leave a truncated United States facing British possessions to the south, north, and west; with the Atlantic seaboard controlled by the Royal Navy, Congress would be forced to agree to terms.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, assumptions about the level of Loyalist support proved wildly optimistic.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Germain ordered Augustine Prevost, the British commander in East Florida, to advance into Georgia in December 1778.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Lieutenant-Colonel Archibald Campbell, an experienced officer, captured Savannah on December 29, 1778.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He recruited a Loyalist militia of nearly 1,100, many of whom allegedly joined only after Campbell threatened to confiscate their property.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Poor motivation and training made them unreliable troops, as demonstrated in their defeat by Patriot militia at the Battle of Kettle Creek on February 14, 1779, although this was offset by British victory at Brier Creek on March 3.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In June 1779, Prevost launched an abortive assault on Charleston, before retreating to Savannah, an operation notorious for widespread looting by British troops that enraged both Loyalists and Patriots.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In October, a joint French and American operation under d'Estaing and General Benjamin Lincoln failed to recapture Savannah.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Prevost was replaced by Lord Cornwallis, who assumed responsibility for Germain's strategy; he soon realized estimates of Loyalist support were considerably over-stated, and he needed far more regular forces.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Reinforced by Clinton, Cornwallis's troops captured Charleston in May 1780, inflicting the most serious Patriot defeat of the war; over 5,000 prisoners were taken and the Continental Army in the south effectively destroyed.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On May 29, Lieutenant-Colonel Banastre Tarleton's mainly Loyalist force routed a Continental Army force nearly three times its size under Colonel Abraham Buford at the Battle of Waxhaws.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The battle is controversial for allegations of a massacre, which were later used as a recruiting tool by the Patriots.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton returned to New York, leaving Cornwallis to oversee the south; despite their success, the two men left barely on speaking terms.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Southern strategy depended on local support, but this was undermined by a series of coercive measures.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Previously, captured Patriots were sent home after swearing not to take up arms against the king; they were now required to fight their former comrades, while the confiscation of Patriot-owned plantations led formerly neutral "grandees" to side with them.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Skirmishes at Williamson's Plantation, Cedar Springs, Rocky Mount, and Hanging Rock signaled widespread resistance to the new oaths throughout South Carolina.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In July 1780, Congress appointed Gates commander in the south; he was defeated at the Battle of Camden on August 16, leaving Cornwallis free to enter North Carolina.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite battlefield success, the British could not control the countryside and Patriot attacks continued; before moving north, Cornwallis sent Loyalist militia under Major Patrick Ferguson to cover his left flank, leaving their forces too far apart to provide mutual support.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In early October, Ferguson was defeated at the Battle of Kings Mountain, dispersing organized Loyalist resistance in the region.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite this, Cornwallis continued into North Carolina hoping for Loyalist support, while Washington replaced Gates with General Nathanael Greene in December 1780.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Greene divided his army, leading his main force southeast pursued by Cornwallis; a detachment was sent southwest under Daniel Morgan, who defeated Tarleton's British Legion at Cowpens on January 17, 1781, nearly eliminating it as a fighting force.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Patriots now held the initiative in the south, with the exception of a raid on Richmond led by Benedict Arnold in January 1781.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Greene led Cornwallis on a series of countermarches around North Carolina; by early March, the British were exhausted and short of supplies and Greene felt strong enough to fight the Battle of Guilford Court House on March 15.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although victorious, Cornwallis suffered heavy casualties and retreated to Wilmington, North Carolina, seeking supplies and reinforcements.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Patriots now controlled most of the Carolinas and Georgia outside the coastal areas; after a minor reversal at the Battle of Hobkirk's Hill, they captured Fort Balfour on April 13 and recaptured Fort Watson and Fort Motte on April 15.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 6, Brigadier General Andrew Pickens captured Augusta, leaving the British in Georgia confined to Charleston and Savannah.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The assumption Loyalists would do most of the fighting left the British short of troops and battlefield victories came at the cost of losses they could not replace.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite halting Greene's advance at the Battle of Eutaw Springs on September 8, Cornwallis withdrew to Charleston with little to show for his campaign.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] From the beginning of the war, Bernardo de Gálvez, the Governor of Spanish Louisiana, allowed the Americans to import supplies and munitions into New Orleans, then ship them to Pittsburgh.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This provided an alternative transportation route for the Continental Army, bypassing the British blockade of the Atlantic Coast.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In February 1778, an expedition of militia to destroy British military supplies in settlements along the Cuyahoga River was halted by adverse weather.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Later in the year, a second campaign was undertaken to seize the Illinois Country from the British.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Virginia militia, *Canadien* settlers, and Indian allies commanded by Colonel George Rogers Clark captured Kaskaskia on July 4 and then secured Vincennes, though Vincennes was recaptured by Quebec Governor Henry Hamilton.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Spanish-aligned fur trader Francis Vigo, an American sympathizer, alerted Clark to the threat posed to his control of the west by Hamilton's position and in early 1779, the Virginians counter-attacked in the siege of Fort Vincennes and took Hamilton prisoner.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clark secured western British Quebec as the American Northwest Territory in the Treaty of Paris as the Revolutionary War came to an end.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Spain joined France's war against Britain in the Anglo-French War in 1779, their treaty specifically excluded Spanish military action in North America.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Later that year, however, Gálvez initiated offensive operations against British outposts.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] First, he cleared British garrisons in Baton Rouge, Louisiana, Fort Bute, and Natchez, Mississippi, and captured five forts.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In doing so, Gálvez opened navigation on the Mississippi River north to the American settlement in Pittsburgh.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On May 25, 1780, British Colonel Henry Bird invaded Kentucky as part of a wider operation to clear American resistance from Quebec to the Gulf Coast.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Their advance on New Orleans was repelled by Spanish Governor Gálvez's offensive on Mobile.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Simultaneous British attacks were repulsed on St.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Louis by the Spanish Lieutenant Governor de Leyba, and on the Virginia County courthouse in Cahokia, Illinois, by Lieutenant Colonel Clark.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British initiative under Bird from Detroit was ended at the rumored approach of Clark.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The scale of violence in the Licking River Valley, was extreme "even for frontier standards." It led to English and German settlements, who joined Clark's militia when the British and their hired German soldiers withdrew to the Great Lakes.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Americans responded with a major offensive along the Mad River in August which met with some success in the Battle of Piqua but did not end Indian raids.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] French soldier Augustin de La Balme led a Canadian militia in an attempt to capture Detroit, but they dispersed when Miami natives led by Little Turtle attacked the encamped settlers on November 5.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The war in the west stalemated with the British garrison sitting in Detroit and the Virginians expanding westward settlements north of the Ohio River in the face of British-allied Indian resistance.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In 1781, Galvez and Pollock campaigned east along the Gulf Coast to secure West Florida, including British-held Mobile and Pensacola.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Spanish operations impaired the British supply of armaments to British Indian allies, which effectively suspended a military alliance to attack settlers between the Mississippi River and the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In 1782, large scale retaliations between settlers and Native Americans in the region included the Gnadenhutten massacre and the Crawford expedition.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The 1782 Battle of Blue Licks was one of the last major engagements of the war.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] News of the treaty between Great Britain and the United States arrived late that year.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] By this time, about 7% of Kentucky settlers had been killed in battles against Native Americans, contrasted with 1% of the population killed in the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Lingering resentments led to continued fighting in the west after the war officially ended.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton spent most of 1781 based in New York City; he failed to construct a coherent operational strategy, partly due to his difficult relationship with Admiral Marriot Arbuthnot.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In Charleston, Cornwallis independently developed an aggressive plan for a campaign in Virginia, which he hoped would isolate Greene's army in the Carolinas and cause the collapse of Patriot resistance in the South.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This strategy was approved by Lord Germain in London, but neither informed Clinton.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington and Rochambeau discussed their options: Washington wanted to attack the British in New York, and Rochambeau wanted to attack them in Virginia, where Cornwallis's forces were less established.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington eventually gave way, and Lafayette took a combined Franco-American force into Virginia.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton misinterpreted his movements as preparations for an attack on New York and instructed Cornwallis to establish a fortified sea base, where the Royal Navy could evacuate British troops to help defend New York.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Lafayette entered Virginia, Cornwallis complied with Clinton's orders and withdrew to Yorktown, where he constructed strong defenses and awaited evacuation.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] An agreement by the Spanish Navy to defend the French West Indies allowed Admiral François Joseph Paul de Grasse to relocate to the Atlantic seaboard, a move Arbuthnot did not anticipate.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This provided Lafayette naval support, while the failure of previous combined operations at Newport and Savannah meant their coordination was planned more carefully.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite repeated urging from his subordinates, Cornwallis made no attempt to engage Lafayette before he could establish siege lines.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Expecting to be withdrawn within a few days, he also abandoned the outer defenses, which were promptly occupied by the besiegers and hastened British defeat.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On August 31, a Royal Navy fleet under Thomas Graves left New York for Yorktown.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After landing troops and munitions for the besiegers on August 30, de Grasse remained in Chesapeake Bay and intercepted him on September 5; although the Battle of the Chesapeake was indecisive in terms of losses, Graves was forced to retreat, leaving Cornwallis isolated.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] An attempted breakout over the York River at Gloucester Point failed due to bad weather.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Under heavy bombardment with dwindling supplies, on October 16 Cornwallis sent emissaries to General Washington to negotiate surrender; after twelve hours of negotiations, the terms of surrender were finalized the following day.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Responsibility for defeat was the subject of fierce public debate between Cornwallis, Clinton, and Germain.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton ultimately took most of the blame and spent the rest of his life in relative obscurity.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Subsequent to Yorktown, American forces were assigned to supervise the armistice between Washington and Clinton made to facilitate British departure following the January 1782 law of Parliament forbidding any further British offensive action in North America.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British-American negotiations in Paris led to signed preliminary agreements in November 1782, which acknowledged US independence.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The enacted Congressional war objective, a British withdrawal from North America and cession of these regions to the US, was completed in stages in East Coast cities.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In the US South, Generals Greene and Wayne observed the British removing their troops from Charleston on December 14, 1782.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Loyalist provincial militias of whites and free Blacks and Loyalists with slaves were transported to Nova Scotia and the British West Indies.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Native American allies of the British and some freed Blacks were left to escape unaided through the American lines.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On April 9, 1783, Washington issued orders that "all acts of hostility" were to cease immediately.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] That same day, by arrangement with Washington, Carleton issued a similar order to British troops.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As directed by a Congressional resolution of May 26, 1783, all non-commissioned officers and enlisted were furloughed "to their homes" until the "definitive treaty of peace", when they would be automatically discharged.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The US armies were directly disbanded in the field as of Washington's General Orders on June 2, 1783.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Once the Treaty of Paris was signed with Britain on September 3, 1783, Washington resigned as commander-in-chief of the Continental Army.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The last British occupation of New York City ended on November 25, 1783, with the departure of Clinton's replacement, General Sir Guy Carleton.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To win their insurrection, Washington and the Continental Army needed to outlast the British will to fight.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To restore British America, the British had to defeat the Continental Army quickly and compel the Second Continental Congress to retract its claim to self-governance.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Mays of The Citadel identifies three separate types of warfare during the Revolutionary War.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The first was a colonial conflict in which objections to imperial trade regulation were as significant as taxation policy.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The second was a civil war between American Patriots, American Loyalists, and those who preferred to remain neutral.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Particularly in the south, many battles were fought between Patriots and Loyalists with no British involvement, leading to divisions that continued after independence was achieved.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The third element was a global war between France, Spain, the Dutch Republic, and Britain, with America serving as one of several different war theaters.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After entering the Revolutionary War in 1778, France provided the Americans money, weapons, soldiers, and naval assistance, while French troops fought under US command in North America.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] While Spain did not formally join the war in America, they provided access to the Mississippi River and captured British possessions on the Gulf of Mexico that denied bases to the Royal Navy, retook Menorca and besieged Gibraltar in Europe.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Although the Dutch Republic was no longer a major power prior to 1774, they still dominated the European carrying trade, and Dutch merchants made large profits by shipping French-supplied munitions to the Patriots.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] This ended when Britain declared war in December 1780, and the conflict proved disastrous to the Dutch economy.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Americans stood to benefit if the Continental Army remained intact and the armed conflict became a protracted war.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] British supply lines were long, replacement of troops difficult, and the war was expensive.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Colonial populations were largely prosperous and depended on local production for food and supplies rather than on imports from Britain.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The thirteen colonies were spread across most of North American Atlantic seaboard, stretching 1,000 miles.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Most colonial farms were remote from the seaports, and control of four or five major ports did not give Britain control over American inland areas.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Each state had established internal distribution systems.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Motivation was also a major asset: each colonial capital had its own newspapers and printers, and the Patriots enjoyed more popular support than the Loyalists.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Britain hoped that the Loyalists would do much of the fighting, but found that the Loyalists did not engage as significantly as they had hoped.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When the Revolutionary War began, the Second Continental Congress lacked a professional army or navy.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, each of the colonies had a long-established system of local militia, which were combat-tested in support of British regulars in the French and Indian War.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The colonial state legislatures independently funded and controlled their local militias.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Militiamen were lightly armed, had little training, and usually did not have uniforms.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Their units served for only a few weeks or months at a time and lacked the training and discipline of more experienced soldiers.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Local county militias were reluctant to travel far from home and were unavailable for extended operations.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To compensate for this, the Continental Congress established a regular force known as the Continental Army on June 14, 1775, which proved to be the origin of the modern United States Army, and appointed Washington as its commander-in-chief.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, it suffered significantly from the lack of an effective training program and from largely inexperienced officers.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] One of Washington's most successful general officer recruits was Steuben, a veteran of the Prussian general staff who wrote the Revolutionary War Drill Manual.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Both sides used partisan warfare, but the state militias effectively suppressed Loyalist activity when British regulars were not in the area.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington designed the overall military strategy in cooperation with Congress, established the principle of civilian supremacy in military affairs, personally recruited his senior officer corps, and kept the states focused on a common goal.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington initially employed the inexperienced officers and untrained troops in Fabian strategies rather than risk frontal assaults against Britain's professional forces.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Over the course of the war, Washington lost more battles than he won, but he never surrendered his troops and maintained a fighting force in the face of British field armies.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] By prevailing European standards, the armies in America were relatively small, limited by lack of supplies and logistics.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The British were constrained by the logistical difficulty of transporting troops across the Atlantic and their dependence on local supplies.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington never directly commanded more than 17,000 men, and the combined Franco-American army in the decisive American victory at Yorktown was only about 19,000.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] At the beginning of 1776, Patriot forces consisted of 20,000 men, with two-thirds in the Continental Army and the other third in the state militias.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] About 250,000 American men served as regulars or as militia for the revolutionary cause during the war, but there were never more than 90,000 men under arms at any time.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On the whole, American officers never equaled their British opponents in tactics and maneuvers, and they lost most of the pitched battles.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The great successes at Boston (1776), Saratoga (1777), and Yorktown (1781) were won by trapping the British far from base with a greater number of troops.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After 1778, Washington's army was transformed into a more disciplined and effective force, mostly as a product of Baron von Steuben's military training.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After the Battle of Monmouth, Washington came to realize that saving entire towns was not necessary, but preserving his army and keeping the revolutionary spirit alive was more important.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Although the Continental Congress was responsible for the war effort and provided supplies to the troops, Washington took it upon himself to pressure Congress and the state legislatures to provide the essentials of war; there was never nearly enough.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Congress evolved in its committee oversight and established the Board of War, which included members of the military.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Because the Board of War was also a committee ensnared with its own internal procedures, Congress also created the post of Secretary of War, appointing Major General Benjamin Lincoln to the position in February 1781.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington worked closely with Lincoln to coordinate civilian and military authorities and took charge of training and supplying the army.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] During the first summer of the war, Washington began outfitting schooners and other small seagoing vessels to prey on ships supplying the British in Boston.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Second Continental Congress established the Continental Navy on October 13, 1775, and appointed Esek Hopkins as its first commander; for most of the war, the Continental Navy included only a handful of small frigates and sloops, supported by privateers.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On November 10, 1775, Congress authorized the creation of the Continental Marines, which ultimately evolved into the United States Marine Corps.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] John Paul Jones became the first American naval hero when he captured HMS *Drake* on April 24, 1778, the first victory for any American military vessel in British waters.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The last such victory was by the frigate USS *Alliance*, commanded by Captain John Barry.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On March 10, 1783, the *Alliance* outgunned HMS *Sybil* in a 45-minute duel while escorting Spanish gold from Havana to the Congress in Philadelphia.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After Yorktown, all US Navy ships were sold or given away; it was the first time in America's history that it had no fighting forces on the high seas.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Congress primarily commissioned privateers to reduce costs and to take advantage of the large proportion of colonial sailors found in the British Empire.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In total, they included 1,700 ships that successfully captured 2,283 enemy ships to damage the British effort and to enrich themselves with the proceeds from the sale of cargo and the ship itself.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] About 55,000 sailors served aboard American privateers during the war.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] At the beginning of the war, the Americans had no major international allies, since most nation-states waited to see how the conflict unfolded.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Over time, the Continental Army established its military credibility.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The decisive American victory at Saratoga convinced France, which was already a long-time rival of Britain, to offer the Americans the Treaty of Amity and Commerce.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The two nations also agreed to a defensive Treaty of Alliance to protect their trade and also guaranteed American independence from Britain.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To engage the United States as a French ally militarily, the treaty was conditioned on Britain initiating a war on France to stop it from trading with the US.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Spain and the Dutch Republic were invited to join by both France and the United States in the treaty, but neither was responsive to the request.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On June 13, 1778, France declared war on Great Britain, and it invoked the French military alliance with the US, which ensured additional US private support for French possessions in the Caribbean.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington worked closely with the soldiers and navy that France would send to America, primarily through Lafayette on his staff.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] French assistance made critical contributions required to defeat Cornwallis at Yorktown in 1781.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The British military had considerable experience fighting in North America.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, in previous conflicts they benefited from local logistics and support from the colonial militia.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In the American Revolutionary War, reinforcements had to come from Europe, and maintaining large armies over such distances was extremely complex; ships could take three months to cross the Atlantic, and orders from London were often outdated by the time they arrived.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Prior to the conflict, the colonies were largely autonomous economic and political entities, with no centralized area of ultimate strategic importance.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] This meant that, unlike Europe where the fall of a capital city often ended wars, that in America continued even after the loss of major settlements such as Philadelphia, the seat of Congress, New York, and Charleston.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] British power was reliant on the Royal Navy, whose dominance allowed them to resupply their own expeditionary forces while preventing access to enemy ports.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, the majority of the American population was agrarian, rather than urban; supported by the French navy and blockade runners based in the Dutch Caribbean, their economy was able to survive.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Lord North, Prime Minister since 1770, delegated control of the war in North America to Lord George Germain and the Earl of Sandwich, who was head of the Royal Navy from 1771 to 1782.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Defeat at Saratoga in 1777 made it clear the revolt would not be easily suppressed, especially after the Franco-American alliance of February 1778.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] With Spain also expected to join the conflict, the Royal Navy needed to prioritize either the war in America or in Europe; Germain advocated the former, Sandwich the latter.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] North initially backed the Southern strategy attempting to exploit divisions between the mercantile north and slave-owning south, but after the defeat of Yorktown, he was forced to accept that this policy had failed.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] It was clear the war was lost, although the Royal Navy forced the French to relocate their fleet to the Caribbean in November 1781 and resumed a close blockade of American trade.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The resulting economic damage and rising inflation meant the US was now eager to end the war, while France was unable to provide further loans; Congress could no longer pay its soldiers.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The geographical size of the colonies and limited manpower meant the British could not simultaneously conduct military operations and occupy territory without local support.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Debate persists over whether their defeat was inevitable; one British statesman described it as "like trying to conquer a map".
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] While Ferling argues Patriot victory was nothing short of a miracle, Ellis suggests the odds always favored the Americans, especially after Howe squandered the chance of a decisive British success in 1776, an "opportunity that would never come again".
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The US military history speculates the additional commitment of 10,000 fresh troops in 1780 would have placed British victory "within the realm of possibility".
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The expulsion of France from North America in 1763 led to a drastic reduction in British troop levels in the colonies; in 1775, there were only 8,500 regular soldiers among a civilian population of 2.8 million.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The bulk of military resources in the Americas were focused on defending sugar islands in the Caribbean; Jamaica alone generated more revenue than all thirteen American colonies combined.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] With the end of the Seven Years' War, the permanent army in Britain was also cut back, which resulted in administrative difficulties when the war began a decade later.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Over the course of the war, there were four separate British commanders-in-chief.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The first was Thomas Gage, appointed in 1763, whose initial focus was establishing British rule in former French areas of Canada.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Many in London blamed the revolt on his failure to take firm action earlier, and he was relieved after the heavy losses incurred at the Battle of Bunker Hill.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] His replacement was Sir William Howe, a member of the Whig faction in Parliament who opposed the policy of coercion advocated by Lord North; Cornwallis, who later surrendered at Yorktown, was one of many senior officers who initially refused to serve in North America.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The 1775 campaign showed the British overestimated the capabilities of their own troops and underestimated the colonial militia, requiring a reassessment of tactics and strategy, and allowing the Patriots to take the initiative.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Howe's responsibility is still debated; despite receiving large numbers of reinforcements, Bunker Hill seems to have permanently affected his self-confidence and lack of tactical flexibility meant he often failed to follow up opportunities.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Many of his decisions were attributed to supply problems, such as his failure to pursue Washington's beaten army.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Having lost the confidence of his subordinates, he was recalled after Burgoyne surrendered at Saratoga.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Following the failure of the Carlisle Commission, British policy changed from treating the Patriots as subjects who needed to be reconciled to enemies who had to be defeated.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In 1778, Howe was replaced by Sir Henry Clinton.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Regarded as an expert on tactics and strategy, like his predecessors Clinton was handicapped by chronic supply issues.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In addition, Clinton's strategy was compromised by conflict with political superiors in London and his colleagues in North America, especially Admiral Mariot Arbuthnot, replaced in early 1781 by Rodney.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] He was neither notified nor consulted when Germain approved Cornwallis's invasion of the south in 1781 and delayed sending him reinforcements believing the bulk of Washington's army was still outside New York City.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After the surrender at Yorktown, Clinton was relieved by Carleton, whose major task was to oversee the evacuation of Loyalists and British troops from Savannah, Charleston, and New York City.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] During the 18th century, states commonly hired foreign soldiers, including Britain.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When it became clear additional troops were needed to suppress the revolt in America, it was decided to employ professional German soldiers.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] There were several reasons for this, including public sympathy for the Patriot cause, a historical reluctance to expand the British army and the time needed to recruit and train new regiments.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Many smaller states in the Holy Roman Empire had a long tradition of renting their armies to the highest bidder.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The most important was Hesse-Kassel, known as "the Mercenary State".
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The first supply agreements were signed by the North administration in late 1775; 30,000 Germans served in the American War.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Often generically referred to as "Hessians", they included men from many other states, including Hanover and Brunswick.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Sir Henry Clinton recommended recruiting Russian troops whom he rated very highly, having seen them in action against the Ottomans; however, negotiations with Catherine the Great made little progress.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Unlike previous wars their use led to intense political debate in Britain, France, and even Germany, where Frederick the Great refused to provide passage through his territories for troops hired for the American war.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In March 1776, the agreements were challenged in Parliament by Whigs who objected to "coercion" in general, and the use of foreign soldiers to subdue "British subjects".
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The debates were covered in detail by American newspapers; in May 1776 they received copies of the treaties themselves, provided by British sympathizers and smuggled into North America from London.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The prospect of foreign German soldiers being used in the colonies bolstered support for independence, more so than taxation and other acts combined; the King was accused of declaring war on his own subjects, leading to the idea there were now two separate governments.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] By apparently showing Britain was determined to go to war, it made hopes of reconciliation seem naive and hopeless, while the employment of what was regarded as "foreign mercenaries" became one of the charges levelled against George III in the Declaration of Independence.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Hessian reputation within Germany for brutality also increased support for the Patriot cause among German American immigrants.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The presence of over 150,000 German Americans meant both sides felt the German soldiers might be persuaded to desert; one reason Clinton suggested employing Russians was that he felt they were less likely to defect.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When the first German troops arrived on Staten Island in August 1776, Congress approved the printing of handbills, promising land and citizenship to any willing to join the Patriot cause.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The British launched a counter-campaign claiming deserters could be executed.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Desertion among the Germans occurred throughout the war, with the highest rate of desertion occurring between the surrender at Yorktown and the Treaty of Paris.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] German regiments were central to the British war effort; of the estimated 30,000 sent to America, some 13,000 became casualties.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Wealthy Loyalists convinced the British government that most of the colonists were sympathetic toward the Crown; consequently, British military planners relied on recruiting Loyalists, but had trouble recruiting sufficient numbers as the Patriots had widespread support.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Approximately 25,000 Loyalists fought for the British throughout the war.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Although Loyalists constituted about twenty percent of the colonial population, they were concentrated in distinct communities.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Many of them lived among large plantation owners in the Tidewater region and South Carolina.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When the British began probing the backcountry in 1777–1778, they were faced with a major problem: any significant level of organized Loyalist activity required a continued presence of British regulars.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The available manpower that the British had in America was insufficient to protect Loyalist territory and counter American offensives.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Loyalist militias in the South were constantly defeated by neighboring Patriot militia.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Patriot victory at the Battle of Kings Mountain irreversibly impaired Loyalist militia capability in the South.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When the early war policy was administered by Howe, the Crown's need to maintain Loyalist support prevented it from using the traditional revolt suppression methods.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The British cause suffered when their troops ransacked local homes during an aborted attack on Charleston in 1779 that enraged both Patriots and Loyalists.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After Congress rejected the Carlisle Peace Commission in 1778 and Westminster turned to "hard war" during Clinton's command, neutral colonists in the Carolinas often allied with the Patriots.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Conversely, Loyalists gained support when Patriots intimidated suspected Tories by destroying property or tarring and feathering.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] A Loyalist militia unit—the British Legion—provided some of the best troops in British service.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] It was commanded by Tarleton and gained a fearsome reputation in the colonies for "brutality and needless slaughter".
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Women played various roles during the Revolutionary War; they often accompanied their husbands when permitted.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] For example, throughout the war Martha Washington was known to visit and provide aid to her husband George at various American camps.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Women often accompanied armies as camp followers to sell goods and perform necessary tasks in hospitals and camps, and numbered in the thousands during the war.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Women also assumed military roles: some dressed as men to directly support combat, fight, or act as spies on both sides.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Anna Maria Lane joined her husband in the Army.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Virginia General Assembly later cited her bravery: she fought while dressed as a man and "performed extraordinary military services, and received a severe wound at the battle of Germantown ... with the courage of a soldier".
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On April 26, 1777, Sybil Ludington is said to have ridden to alert militia forces to the British's approach; she has been called the "female Paul Revere".
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Whether the ride occurred is questioned.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] A few others disguised themselves as men.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Deborah Sampson fought until her gender was discovered and she was discharged as a result; Sally St.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When war began, the population of the Thirteen Colonies included an estimated 500,000 slaves, predominantly used as labor on Southern plantations.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In November 1775, Lord Dunmore, the royal governor of Virginia, issued a proclamation that promised freedom to any Patriot-owned slaves willing to bear arms.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Although the announcement helped to fill a temporary manpower shortage, white Loyalist prejudice meant recruits were eventually redirected to non-combatant roles.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Loyalists' motive was to deprive Patriot planters of labor rather than to end slavery; Loyalist-owned slaves were returned.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The 1779 Philipsburg Proclamation issued by Clinton extended the offer of freedom to Patriot-owned slaves throughout the colonies.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] It persuaded entire families to escape to British lines, many of which were employed growing food for the army by removing the requirement for military service.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] While Clinton organized the Black Pioneers, he also ensured fugitive slaves were returned to Loyalist owners with orders that they were not to be punished.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] As the war progressed, service as regular soldiers in British units became increasingly common; Black Loyalists formed two regiments of the Charleston garrison in 1783.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Estimates of the numbers who served the British during the war vary from 25,000 to 50,000, excluding those who escaped during wartime.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Thomas Jefferson estimated that Virginia may have lost 30,000 slaves to escapes.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In South Carolina, nearly 25,000 slaves (about 30 percent of the enslaved population) either fled, migrated, or died, which significantly disrupted the plantation economies both during and after the war.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Black Patriots were barred from the Continental Army until Washington convinced Congress in January 1778 that there was no other way to replace losses from disease and desertion.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The 1st Rhode Island Regiment formed in February included former slaves whose owners were compensated; however, only 140 of its 225 soldiers were Black and recruitment stopped in June 1788.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Ultimately, around 5,000 African Americans served in the Continental Army and Navy in a variety of roles, while another 4,000 were employed in Patriot militia units, aboard privateers, or as teamsters, servants, and spies.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After the war, a small minority received land grants or Congressional pensions; many others were returned to their masters post-war despite earlier promises of freedom.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] As a Patriot victory became increasingly likely, the treatment of Black Loyalists became a point of contention; after the surrender of Yorktown in 1781, Washington insisted all escapees be returned but Cornwallis refused.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In 1782 and 1783, around 8,000 to 10,000 freed Blacks were evacuated by the British from Charleston, Savannah, and New York; some moved onto London, while 3,000 to 4,000 settled in Nova Scotia.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] White Loyalists transported 15,000 enslaved Blacks to Jamaica and the Bahamas.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The free Black Loyalists who migrated to the British West Indies included regular soldiers from Dunmore's Ethiopian Regiment, and those from Charleston who helped garrison the Leeward Islands.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Most Native Americans east of the Mississippi River were affected by the war, and many tribes were divided over how to respond.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] A few tribes were friendly with the colonists, but most Natives opposed the union of the Colonies as a potential threat to their territory.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Approximately 13,000 Natives fought on the British side, with the largest group coming from tribal factions of the Haudenosaunee Confederacy (*also* Iroquois) who deployed around 1,500 men.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Early in July 1776, Cherokee allies of Britain attacked the short-lived Washington District of North Carolina.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Their defeat splintered both Cherokee settlements and people, and was directly responsible for the rise of the Chickamauga Cherokee, who perpetrated the Cherokee–American wars against American settlers for decades after hostilities with Britain ended.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Muscogee and other allies of Britain fought against Americans in Georgia and South Carolina.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In 1778, a force of 800 Muscogee destroyed American settlements along the Broad River in Georgia.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Muscogee warriors also joined Thomas Brown's raids into South Carolina and assisted Britain during the siege of Savannah.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Many Native Americans were involved in the fight between Britain and Spain on the Gulf Coast and along the British side of the Mississippi River.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Thousands of Muscogee, Chickasaw, and Choctaw fought in major battles such as the Battle of Fort Charlotte, the Battle of Mobile, and the siege of Pensacola.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Haudenosaunee Confederacy (*also* Iroquois) was shattered as a result of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Seneca, Onondaga, and Cayuga tribes sided with the British; members of the Mohawks fought on both sides; and many Tuscarora and Oneida sided with the Americans.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To retaliate against raids on American settlement by Loyalists and their Indian allies, the Continental Army dispatched the Sullivan Expedition throughout New York to debilitate the Iroquois tribes that had sided with the British.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Mohawk leaders Akiatonharónkwen (*also* Joseph Louis Cook) and Thayendanegea (*also* Joseph Brant) sided with the Americans and the British respectively, which further exacerbated the split.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In the western theater, conflicts between settlers and Native Americans led to lingering distrust.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In the 1783 Treaty of Paris, Great Britain ceded control of the disputed lands between the Great Lakes and the Ohio River, but Native inhabitants were not a part of the peace negotiations.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Tribes in the Northwest Territory joined as the Western Confederacy and allied with the British to resist American settlement, and their conflict continued after the Revolutionary War as the Northwest Indian War.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The terms presented by the Carlisle Peace Commission in 1778 included acceptance of the principle of self-government.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Parliament would recognize Congress as the governing body, suspend any objectionable legislation, surrender its right to local colonial taxation, and discuss including American representatives in the House of Commons.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In return, all property confiscated from Loyalists would be returned, British debts honored, and locally enforced martial law accepted.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, Congress demanded either immediate recognition of independence or the withdrawal of all British troops; they knew the commission were not authorized to accept these, bringing negotiations to a rapid end.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On February 27, 1782, a Whig motion to end the offensive war in America was carried by 19 votes.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] North resigned, obliging the king to invite Lord Rockingham to form a government; a consistent supporter of the Patriot cause, he made a commitment to US independence a condition of doing so.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] George III reluctantly accepted and the new government took office on March 27, 1782; however, Rockingham died unexpectedly on July 1, and was replaced by Lord Shelburne who acknowledged American independence.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When Lord Rockingham was elevated to Prime Minister, Congress consolidated its diplomatic consuls in Europe into a peace delegation at Paris.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The dean of the delegation was Benjamin Franklin.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] He had become a celebrity in the French Court, but he was also influential in the courts of Prussia and Austria.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Since the 1760s, Franklin had been an organizer of British American inter-colony cooperation, and then served as a colonial lobbyist to Parliament in London.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] John Adams had been consul to the Dutch Republic and was a prominent early New England Patriot.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] John Jay of New York had been consul to Spain and was a past president of the Continental Congress.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] As consul to the Dutch Republic, Henry Laurens had secured a preliminary agreement for a trade agreement.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Although active in the preliminaries, he was not a signer of the conclusive treaty.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Whig negotiators included long-time friend of Franklin David Hartley, and Richard Oswald, who had negotiated Laurens' release from the Tower of London.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Preliminary Peace signed on November 30 met four key Congressional demands: independence, territory up to the Mississippi, navigation rights into the Gulf of Mexico, and fishing rights in Newfoundland.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] British strategy was to strengthen the US sufficiently to prevent France from regaining a foothold in North America, and they had little interest in these proposals.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, divisions between their opponents allowed them to negotiate separately with each to improve their overall position, starting with the American delegation in September 1782.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The French and Spanish sought to improve their position by creating the US dependent on them for support against Britain, thus reversing the losses of 1763.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Both parties tried to negotiate a settlement with Britain excluding the Americans; France proposed setting the western boundary of the US along the Appalachians, matching the British 1763 Proclamation Line.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Spanish suggested additional concessions in the vital Mississippi River Basin, but required the cession of Georgia in violation of the Franco-American alliance.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Key agreements for the United States in obtaining peace included recognition of US independence; all of the territory east of the Mississippi River, north of Florida and south of Canada; and fishing rights in the Grand Banks, off the coast of Newfoundland and in the Gulf of Saint Lawrence.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The United States and Great Britain were each given perpetual access to the Mississippi River.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] An Anglo-American Preliminary Peace was formally entered into in November 1782, and Congress endorsed the settlement on April 15, 1783.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] It announced the achievement of peace with independence, and the conclusive treaty was signed on September 2, 1783, in Paris, effective the following day when Britain signed its treaty with France.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] John Adams, who helped draft the treaty, claimed it represented "one of the most important political events that ever happened on the globe".
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Ratified respectively by Congress and Parliament, the final versions were exchanged in Paris the following spring.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On November 25, the last British troops remaining in the US were evacuated from New York to Halifax.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The expanse of territory that was now the US included millions of sparsely settled acres south of the Great Lakes between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River, much of which was part of Canada.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The tentative colonial migration west became a flood during the war.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Britain's extended post-war policy for the US continued to try to establish an Indian barrier state below the Great Lakes as late as 1814 during the War of 1812.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The formally acquired western American lands continued to be populated by Indigenous tribes that had mostly been British allies.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In practice the British refused to abandon the forts on territory they formally transferred.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Instead, they provisioned military allies for continuing frontier raids and sponsored the Northwest Indian War (1785–1795).
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] British sponsorship of local warfare on the US continued until the Anglo-American Jay Treaty, authored by Hamilton, went into effect on February 29, 1796.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Of the European powers with American colonies adjacent to the newly created US, Spain was most threatened by American independence, and it was correspondingly the most hostile to it.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Its territory adjacent to the US was relatively undefended, so Spanish policy developed a combination of initiatives.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Spanish soft power diplomatically challenged the British territorial cession west to the Mississippi River and the previous northern boundaries of Spanish Florida.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] It imposed a high tariff on American goods, then blocked American settler access to the port of New Orleans.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] At the same time, the Spanish also sponsored war within the US by Indian proxies in its Southwest Territory ceded by France to Britain, then Britain to the Americans.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The total loss of life throughout the conflict is largely unknown.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] As was typical in wars of the era, diseases such as smallpox claimed more lives than battle.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Between 1775 and 1782, a smallpox epidemic throughout North America killed an estimated 130,000.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Historian Joseph Ellis suggests that Washington having his troops inoculated against the disease was one of his most important decisions.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] More than 25,000 Patriots died during active military service.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Of these, approximately 6,800 were killed in battle, while at least 17,000 died from disease.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] A large portion of the latter died while prisoners of war of the British, mostly in the prison ships in New York Harbor.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The number of Patriots seriously wounded or disabled by the war has been estimated at 8,500 to 25,000.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Peckham's study, considered the most definitive, specifically estimates 25,324 Patriot army, navy, and militia deaths, of which 6,824 were killed in combat and 18,500 died of disease or other causes (10,000 in camp, 8,500 as prisoners); wounded were estimated at 8,445.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] These casualties occurred over a total of 1,311 distinct military engagements on land, plus 215 at sea.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The French suffered 2,112 killed in combat in the United States.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Spanish lost 124 killed and 247 wounded in West Florida.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] A British report in 1781 puts their deaths at 6,046 in continental North America (1775–1779) for the Army, thus excluding Germans, Loyalists, and sailors.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Including both soldiers and sailors and counting theaters outside of North America, the total British military death toll (excluding officers) from 1775 to 1783 was 43,633.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Approximately 7,774 Germans died in British service in addition to 4,888 deserters; among those labeled German deserters, however, it is estimated that 1,800 were killed in combat.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The American Revolution set an example to overthrow both monarchy and colonial governments.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The United States has the world's oldest written constitution, which was used as a model in other countries, sometimes word-for-word.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Revolution inspired revolutions in France, Haiti, Latin America, and elsewhere.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Although the Revolution eliminated many forms of inequality, it did little to change the status of women, despite the role they played in winning independence.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Most significantly, it failed to end slavery.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] While many were uneasy over the contradiction of demanding liberty for some, yet denying it to others, the dependence of southern states on slave labor made abolition too great a challenge.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Between 1774 and 1780, many of the states banned the importation of slaves, but the institution itself continued.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In 1782, Virginia passed a law permitting manumission and over the next eight years more than 10,000 slaves were given their freedom.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The number of abolitionist movements greatly increased, and by 1804 all the northern states had outlawed it.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, slavery continued to be a serious social and political issue and caused divisions that would ultimately end in civil war.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The body of historical writings on the American Revolution cite many motivations for the Patriot revolt.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After the first US postage stamp was issued in 1849, the US Postal Service frequently issued commemorative stamps celebrating people and events of the Revolutionary War.
[src:adam-style/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The first such stamp was the Liberty Bell issue of 1926.
